ant’s home</p><p>2. Personal Independence Payment began to replace Disability Living Allowance for people aged 16 to 64 from 8 April 2013. Data includes Disablity Living Allowance reassessment</p><p>3. Employment and Support Allowance was rolled out from October 2008 and Employment and Support Allowance (Incapacity Benefit Reassessment) was rolled out from April 2011</p><p>4. Total number of hearing clearances. Cases cleared at tribunal hearing both oral and paper<br>5. Number of cases adjourned at tribunal hearing<br>6. Number falls between one and five.</p><p>Although care is taken when processing and analysing the data, the details are subject to inaccuracies inherent in any large-scale case management system and are the best data available. The data are a subset of official statistics extracted from the case management system on a different date.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-09-07T15:39:32.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755959/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755959/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755959/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Social Security Benefits: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many appeals against decisions on (a) personal independence payment and (b) employment and support allowance were heard at (i) Blackburn, (ii) Blackpool, (iii) Burnley, (iv) Lancaster and (v) Preston Magistrates' Court in each month between 1 January 2016 and 31 July 2017; and on how many occasions at each venue in each of these months regarding (A) personal independence payment and (B) employment and support allowance hearings were adjourned.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","7000"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755960","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-12","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-12T11:06:40.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755960/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755960/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755960/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Prisoners: Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many reports of (a) anti-Semitism, (b) Islamophobia, (c) racism and (d) homophobia by prisoners have been received in the last two years.","false","Biography information for Ellie Reeves","Lewisham West and Penge","Ellie Reeves","7019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755961","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-11","<p>There is a wide range of occupational training available to prisoners. The prison governor works with their education provider to put in place education and training based on the needs of learners in the establishment and the skills in demand by employers in the areas to which prisoners will be released.</p><p>Prisoners are allocated to relevant education and training based on an assessment of their learning needs and in response to information advice and guidance by a National Careers Service adviser. Allocation to education and training takes account of career aspirations, as well as sentence plans, to ensure that interventions are appropriately prioritised and sequenced with other rehabilitation activities. Individual prisons may also apply their own local criteria.</p><p>We do not collect data centrally on the number of courses that are oversubscribed.</p><p>As set out in the White Paper, “Prison Safety and Reform” published in November 2016, we are empowering prison governors to decide how their establishment’s learning offer is arranged, what curriculum is put in place and who delivers the education and training.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-11T13:22:13.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755961/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755961/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Prisons: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what occupational training is available for prisoners; what the criteria are for subscribing to such training; and to what degree any training is oversubscribed.","false","Biography information for Ellie Reeves","Lewisham West and Penge","Ellie Reeves","7022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755962","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-11","<p>There is currently no national education curriculum for prison education, but work is in hand to introduce a core common curriculum across the prison estate, focusing on maths and English, and using the same awarding bodies for particular types of provision so those starting a course at one prison can bank and build on their progress if they move elsewhere. The curriculum for each prison in England is agreed locally by the prison governor with their Offender Learning and Skills Service provider, drawing from a range of provision that the provider is required to offer.</p><p>In October 2016, we introduced changes to the prison education funding rules to give prison governors more authority to put in place education that meets the needs of prisoners in their establishment. Education Delivery Plans for the academic year that commenced on 1 August 2017 are wholly based on those new funding rules and flexibilities, enabling governors to commission delivery of training that meets more effectively the needs of employers in the areas to which prisoners will be released. As set out in the White Paper, “Prison Safety and Reform” published in November 2016, we are extending governor control still further. <br>Prison governors will be fully responsible for education provision in their prisons once existing contracts end, commissioning the services they think are most appropriate in their individual prison.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-11T13:23:32.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755962/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755962/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755962/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Prisons: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether there is a national curriculum for prison education.","false","Biography information for Ellie Reeves","Lewisham West and Penge","Ellie Reeves","7023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755963","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-07","<p>CICA has a target for 2017/18 to decide 85% of new cases within 12 months of receipt. It is recognised there will always be complex cases which need to take longer, for example if the applicant’s medical treatment is ongoing or their level of recovery is not yet known.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-09-07T14:44:35.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755963/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755963/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755963/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the target time is for the Criminal Injuries Compensation Authority to assess a claim.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","7017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755964","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-11","<p>The spend on offender learning in England was £145.2m in the 2015-16 financial year and £146.7m in 2016-17. These figures exclude a number of private prisons where the operator is responsible for providing education under their contract with Her Majesty's Prison and Probation Service.</p><p>As we announced in last November’s White Paper, we will devolve responsibility for prison education budgets to governors, empowering them to decide how education is organised, what curriculum is delivered and who provides the education.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-11T13:17:27.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755964/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755964/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755964/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Prisons: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much has been spent on education services in prisons over the last two years.","false","Biography information for Ellie Reeves","Lewisham West and Penge","Ellie Reeves","7021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755965","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-12","<p>I refer the Honourable Member to my answers to her on 14<sup>th</sup> July (PQ 3463 and PQ 3452).</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-12T11:03:48.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755965/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755965/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755965/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Hate Crime: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether people convicted for hate crimes receive anti-racist or other relevant education as part of their rehabilitation.","false","Biography information for Ellie Reeves","Lewisham West and Penge","Ellie Reeves","7020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755966","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-10-09","<p>Information on the costs incurred in defending all legal proceedings involving challenges to tribunals fees since 2013 is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-10-09T14:53:04.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755966/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755966/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755966/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the amount spent on legal fees relating to challenges to tribunal fees since 2013.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7026"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755967","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-12","<p>The information requested is not held.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-09-12T11:33:48.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755967/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755967/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755967/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much Civil Service time has been spent on legal challenges to tribunal fees in each year since 2013.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755968","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-11","<p>HMPPS coordinates the Offender Banking Programme in England and Wales which runs in partnership with 6 major UK commercial banks and a leading Building Society in order to give offenders who are soon to be released from custody the opportunity to apply for a basic bank account. Having access to a bank account is vital for access to benefits and to receive pay from employment on release, a key element in helping with the rehabilitation of offenders.</p><p>There are currently 101 prison-bank partnerships, the most recent partnership being made with HMP Berwyn, a large new public sector prison which opened earlier this year. Every resettlement prison has a relationship with a specific bank who offer direct support and guidance on their specific processes to prison staff to enable the opening of accounts.</p><p>On arrival in to custody, staff complete a Basic Custody Screening Tool and information from this indicates that 71% of prisoners have bank accounts. HMPPS does not keep a record of those who have left prison without a bank account. However, around 5,000 accounts per year are opened under the programme. The banks report a high percentage of those accounts subsequently being activated and used on release.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","6934 ; 6935 ; 6936 ; 6937 ; 6938","2017-09-11T16:41:47.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755968/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755968/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/755968/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Prisoners: Bank Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps his Department has taken to ensure that all prisoners are able to open a bank account.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","David Hanson","6933"
