"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756010","Attorney General","false","2017-09-18","<p>Each Department is responsible for defending actions brought against them and makes their own arrangements for doing so. There is no central record of all court cases brought against the Government and therefore it is not possible to identify either the total number of cases or the cost of them.</p><p>However, most central government bodies instruct the Government Legal Department to conduct their litigation. Since the 2010-11 financial year the Government Legal Department has been instructed by government bodies in almost 200,000 cases costing about £570 million (including VAT).</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-09-18T11:35:43.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756010/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756010/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756010/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-09-04","Government Departments: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many court cases the Government has defended since 2010; and what the cost to the public purse was of each such case.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","7101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756011","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-11","<p>The number of offenders found guilty at all courts for offences under S22 Gender Recognition Act 2004 is zero in England and Wales, from 2011 (earliest separately identifiable information available) to 2016.</p><p>Please be aware this is on a principal offence basis. Data prior to 2011 are recorded centrally by MoJ on the Court Proceedings Database as part of a miscellaneous grouping of offences, which cannot be separately analysed.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-09-11T16:59:40.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756011/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756011/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756011/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Gender Recognition Act 2004","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people have been found guilty of offences under section 22 of the Gender Recognition Act 2004 in each year since 2004-05; and how many were fined the maximum amount stipulated for that offence.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","7091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756012","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-12","<p>The information requested is not available, as transgender prisoners are under no obligation to provide a gender recognition certificate if they have one.</p><p>The current Prison Service Instruction on the care and management of transgender offenders, issued in November 2016, sets out expected timescales for convening a transgender case board to consider the appropriate location for holding an individual prisoner. Timescales for transfer to a different prison location will depend upon individual circumstances, including the availability of suitable accommodation.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-09-12T15:32:25.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756012/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756012/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756012/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Prisoners: Gender Recognition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average length of time taken was in each year since 2004-05 to transfer transgender prisoners who (a) did and (b) did not have a gender recognition certificate to prisons which correspond to the gender they identify as having.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","7442"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756013","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-11","<p>The current overarching sentencing guideline on Domestic Violence, issued by the independent Sentencing Council for England and Wales, applies to all offences involving domestic violence, including instances of actual and grievous bodily harm. This guideline makes it clear that the domestic setting can be considered as an aggravating factor for sentencing.</p><p> </p><p>In March, the Sentencing Council launched a consultation on revised guidelines for domestic abuse and intimidatory offences which ran until 30 June. Further information can be found on the Council’s website: <a href="http://www.sentencingcouncil.org.uk/" target="_blank">www.sentencingcouncil.org.uk</a></p><p> </p><p>The Domestic Abuse Bill, announced in the Queen’s Speech, will also contain provisions to protect the victims of domestic violence and abuse.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-09-11T16:55:39.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756013/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756013/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756013/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Domestic Abuse: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will take steps to ensure that actual bodily harm and grievous bodily harm in a domestic setting are included in sentencing guidelines as an aggravating factor.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","7459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756014","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-12","<p>The following tables show: 1) the numbers of fatal incident investigations of transgender prisoners; 2) complaints received about racial equality issues; 3) complaints received relating to prisons; and 4) complaints received about transgender issues:</p><p> </p><p><strong>1) </strong><strong>Fatal incident investigations of transgender prisoners started, by financial year</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>PPO fatal incident investigations started</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-2016</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-2017</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>9</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>2) </strong><strong>Complaints received by the PPO about racial equality issues, by financial year</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Complaints Received</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Eligible for investigation</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>23</p></td><td><p>13</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-2016</p></td><td><p>29</p></td><td><p>15</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-2017</p></td><td><p>12</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>3) </strong><strong>Complaints received relating to prisons, by financial year</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Complaints Received</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Eligible for investigation</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>4,894</p></td><td><p>2,704</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>4,438</p></td><td><p>2,033</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>4,582</p></td><td><p>2,310</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-2016</p></td><td><p>4,3</p></td><td><p>2,288</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-2017</p></td><td><p>4,657</p></td><td><p>2,505</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>4) </strong><strong>Complaints received by the PPO about transgender equality issues, by financial year</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Complaints Received</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Eligible for investigation</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-2013</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-2014</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-2015</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-2016</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-2017</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>4</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>We have been able to provide a consistent time series back to 2012/13. The time required to provide data going back to 1997/98 would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>We do not hold information on the overall proportion of the prison population that made a complaint or the proportion of the estimated transgender prisoner population for the time periods requested. There may be other similar cases where the PPO investigated a death but were not aware of the person having previously identified as transgender and therefore their death would not be included in these figures.</p><p> </p><p>The Government believes that prisons should be places of safety and reform. We welcome the work that the PPO has done to prevent self-inflicted deaths in custody, promote equality and inclusion, and improve safety in prisons more generally.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","7087 ; 7089 ; 7090","2017-09-12T11:12:34.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756014/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756014/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756014/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Prisoners: Gender Recognition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many complaints related to transgender equality issues in prisons the Prisons and Probation Ombudsman received in each year since 1997-98; and what those figures represent as a proportion of the estimated transgender prisoner population in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","7390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756015","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-11","<p>The welfare of the child is the court’s paramount concern when making any decision about their upbringing, including with whom the child is to live or spend time. In all cases where a parent applies to the family court for a child arrangements order, the Children and Family Court Advisory and Support Service (Cafcass) in England and Cafcass Cymru in Wales undertake safeguarding checks with the police and relevant local authority children’s services. Relevant information about risk, including from domestic abuse, is reported to the court in writing prior to the first hearing to inform safe decision-making.</p><p>In determining the child’s welfare needs the court will apply the factors set out in the ‘welfare checklist’ in the Children Act 1989. One of those factors concerns any harm the child has suffered or is at risk of suffering, which would include any harm from witnessing domestic abuse.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-09-11T16:50:17.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756015/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756015/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756015/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Family Courts: Domestic Abuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the fact that a child has witnessed domestic violence is taken into account when a family court makes directions in child contact proceedings.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","7395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756016","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Attorney General for Northern Ireland issued a Note of Appeal following the High Court ruling providing temporary authorisation for a celebrant to perform a legally valid and binding humanist wedding ceremony. The Attorney General for Northern Ireland exercises his functions independently. Marriage is an entirely devolved matter in Northern Ireland.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-09-13T10:22:03.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756016/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756016/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756016/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-09-04","Marriage: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, with reference to the case Smyth 2017 No. 038954 on legal recognition for humanist marriages in Northern Ireland, what effect the absence of a Northern Ireland Executive has on the Government of Northern Ireland's authority to continue to contest that case; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","7486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756017","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Northern Ireland Office does not hold the data requested as matters relating to marriage are devolved in Northern Ireland.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-09-13T10:23:14.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756017/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756017/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756017/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-09-04","Marriage: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what information the Government holds on how much the (a) Department of Finance and Registrar General's Office and (b) Office of the Northern Ireland Attorney General have spent contesting case Smyth 2017 No. 038954 on legal recognition of humanist marriages in Northern Ireland at the (i) High Court and (ii) Court of Appeal.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","7484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756018","Prime Minister","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Government has had discussions with the devolved administrations about the inquiry. The Government is consulting on the format, scope and sponsorship of the inquiry until 18 October, and will update the House after the consultation.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-09-07T12:10:00.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756018/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756018/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756018/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-09-04","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, what discussions she has had with the devolved administrations on the terms of reference of an inquiry into the contaminated blood scandal; and if she will publish all correspondence with devolved administrations on that inquiry.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","7209"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756019","Prime Minister","false","2017-09-12","<p>A reply has been sent.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-09-12T14:22:50.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756019/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756019/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756019/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-09-04","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, on what date she plans to respond to the letter of 12 July 2017 from the hon. Member for Glasgow East inviting her to visit Glasgow.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756020","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>Scotland Office Ministers regularly meet with representatives of the sector to listen, exchange views and address concerns and will continue to do so to ensure the sector can take full advantage of the new opportunities that Brexit will bring.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-09-11T12:16:31.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756020/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756020/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756020/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-04","Free Movement of People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what discussions he has had with representatives of the Scottish hospitality sector on the effect of restricted freedom of movement after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756021","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government is committed to supporting the development of a world-leading decommissioning industry. We have already invested in the Oil and Gas Technology Centre through the Aberdeen City Region deal, with the aim of becoming a global centre for solving offshore mature basin, subsea and decommissioning technology challenges.</p><p> </p><p>But whilst a number of UK companies have been successful in winning decommissioning contracts, no UK port currently has the ultra-deep water facilities needed to directly accommodate the fully-loaded heavy lift vessels commonly used for decommissioning large platforms.</p><p> </p><p>The Government intends to take forward scoping work to examine the market failure to deliver these facilities, and potential options for intervention to ensure that the UK is able to effectively compete for forthcoming decommissioning projects. I’d be happy to meet the hon Member to discuss this work further.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-09-12T11:58:46.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756021/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756021/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756021/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-04","Ports: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what plans the Government has to deliver an ultra deep water port on the East Coast of Scotland.","false","Biography information for Andrew Bowie","West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine","Andrew Bowie","7194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756022","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>Ministers and officials regularly meet with a wide range of stakeholders on a variety of issues to ensure that Scotland has a voice in Westminster. The Government publishes a list of all ministerial meetings with external bodies on departmental business on a quarterly basis.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-09-07T14:58:45.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756022/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756022/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756022/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-04","Citizens Advice Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, (a) on which date he last met representatives of Citizens Advice Scotland and (b) what issues were discussed.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","6983"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756023","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>I have not visited a food bank in my capacity as Secretary of State for Scotland.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","8082","2017-09-07T15:00:17.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756023/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756023/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756023/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-04","Food Banks: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, on which date he last visited a food bank.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","6984"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756024","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>I currently have no plans to visit a food bank in my capacity as Secretary of State for Scotland in September 2017.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-09-07T15:01:08.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756024/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756024/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756024/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-04","Food Banks: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, whether he plans to visit a food bank in the month of September 2017.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","6985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756025","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>Social media activity which ran in March 2017 reached all adults in Scotland, male and female. Independent research revealed that women in Scotland are less aware of the work and responsibilities held by UK Government and are interested in finding out more. With that in mind, the Scotland Office also ran Childcare Choices activity, which was promoted to women aged 18-35, and Scotland’s two governments working together, which was promoted to women aged 18-60.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","7440","2017-09-11T12:15:33.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756025/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756025/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756025/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-04","Scotland Office: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, pursuant to the Answer of 17 July 2017 to Question 3978, what the differences were in the advertisements aimed at the different genders.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","7439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756026","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>Social media activity which ran in March 2017 reached all adults in Scotland, male and female. Independent research revealed that women in Scotland are less aware of the work and responsibilities held by UK Government and are interested in finding out more. With that in mind, the Scotland Office also ran Childcare Choices activity, which was promoted to women aged 18-35, and Scotland’s two governments working together, which was promoted to women aged 18-60.</p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell","7439","2017-09-11T12:15:33.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756026/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756026/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756026/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-04","Scotland Office: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, pursuant to the Answer of 17 July 2017 to Question 3978, what age ranges were targeted by his social media spending.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","7440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756027","Scotland Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>I am in regular contact with the Secretary of State for the Home Department on a range of immigration issues.</p><p> </p><p>The United Kingdom, and particularly Scotland, have long historical ties with Malawi. Many people and organisations across Scotland, including the Scotland-Malawi Partnership, have strong links and provide support to groups in Malawi. I have visited Malawi twice as a UK Government Minister, and have seen for myself the great work that we can achieve together on a number of projects.</p><p> </p><p>The Scotland-Malawi Partnership may sponsor visas, and has raised the issue with officials in the Home Office and UK Visas and Immigration (UKVI), who have explored how visa applications can be properly prepared, although all applications must comply with immigration rules.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-09-12T12:00:13.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756027/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756027/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756027/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-09-04","Visas: Malawi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, whether he has had discussions with the Home Secretary on the visa process for the issue of visas to Malawians visiting the UK; and what representations he has received on that process.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756028","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-12","<p>A full economic appraisal has been carried out by HS2 Ltd. for the evaluation of the Phase 1/2a rolling stock fleet mix options in line with the HS2 Business Case modelling framework. The cost-benefit analysis confirmed the procurement of a single fleet of classic (or conventional) compatible trains is expected to deliver similar value for money to that of a mixed fleet solution.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-12T12:43:52.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756028/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756028/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756028/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what cost-benefit analysis he has made of the High Speed 2 rolling stock procurement of a (a) mixed fleet of classic compatible and captive and (b) single fleet of classic compatible trains.","false","Biography information for Iain Stewart","Milton Keynes South","Iain Stewart","7384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756029","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government recognises electrically assisted pedal cycles as an effective alternative to commuting by car, and will continue to promote them as part of our ambition to double cycling by 2025.</p><p> </p><p>The Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy, published in April 2017, sets out the Government's plans to promote all forms of cycling. It also explains how a total of £1.2 billion may be spent on this between 2016 and 2021.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-11T10:00:06.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756029/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756029/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756029/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Electric Vehicles: Bicycles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to increase the use of electric bicycles as an alternative to commuting by car.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","7411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756030","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>As with all local cycling infrastructure, local authorities are best placed to promote cycle paths in their area, which offer cyclists an alternative to cycling in the carriageway.</p><p> </p><p>However, the decision to use a path will depend on the individual cyclist. While they can be attractive to some cyclists, particularly less confident cyclists, cycle paths may not always be convenient for experienced cyclists.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-11T09:46:30.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756030/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756030/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756030/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Cycleways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps the Government is taking to promote the use of cycle paths.","false","Biography information for Mims Davies","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","7420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756031","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government is committed to tackling congestion and improving air quality across the UK. High quality and accessible public transport will play a key role in this, alongside other forms of sustainable transport such as cycling and walking. Our rail plans are seeing the largest investment in the railway since Victorian times, which will help make rail travel more attractive through state-of-the-art new trains and stations, together with more and faster services. The Bus Services Act, which received Royal Assent in April 2017, gives local authorities a further range of tools, such as partnership working and franchising, to deliver service improvements for bus passengers, aiming to drive up bus use and help cut congestion. Our Cycling and Walking Strategy, published in April 2017 identified £1.2bn of investment in cycling and walking from 2016-21.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-12T07:42:44.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756031/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756031/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756031/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Public Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps the Government is taking to encourage people to use public transport in order to reduce congestion and its associated effect on air quality.","false","Biography information for Mims Davies","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","7418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756032","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>We do not yet have data on how many electric vehicles have been registered since 1 April 2017, the date from which the new VED system applies. However, 5,274 battery electric cars were registered in the first four months of 2017, compared to 10,242 in the whole of 2016.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-09-12T10:04:19.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756032/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756032/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756032/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Electric Vehicles: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment has been made of the treatment of electric vehicles with a list price of more than £40,000 under the new vehicle excise duty system on the uptake of electric vehicles.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","7434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756033","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Government does not monitor speed limits, as traffic authorities set local speed limits in situations where local needs and conditions suggest a speed limit which is lower than the national speed limit. The Department has issued guidance to local highway authorities on setting local speed limits, which can be viewed online at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/setting-local-speed-limits" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/setting-local-speed-limits</a></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-11T12:20:10.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756033/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756033/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756033/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Speed Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps the Government is taking to monitor speed limits and ensure that they are appropriate.","false","Biography information for Mims Davies","Eastleigh","Mims Davies","7424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756034","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The provisions of Regulation 1071/2009 have been directly applicable in the UK since 2011.</p><p> </p><p>Following a recent DVSA decision letter to a community transport operator about their non-compliance with legal operating requirements, my Department issued a 31 July letter to permit-issuing bodies to clarify principles that they should have regard to.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport intends to conduct a public consultation in the autumn, which will set out the changes needed to guidance and legislation, on the issue and use of section 19 and section 22 permits. The consultation will be accompanied by an Impact Assessment.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-11T11:22:05.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756034/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756034/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756034/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Transport: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the impact of interpreting into UK law the EU directives on operator licensing on (a) community transport providers and (b) isolated individuals and rural communities.","false","Biography information for Mr Ranil Jayawardena","North East Hampshire","Mr Ranil Jayawardena","7450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756035","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-07","<p>Officials are in dialogue with East Midlands Trains to ensure that any future fleet changes secure the specified passenger service requirement.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-07T13:49:51.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756035/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756035/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756035/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","East Midlands Rail Franchise: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how he plans to ensure the reliability of services for passengers on the East Midlands franchise during the period when the InterCity125 trains are overhauled in 2019 to 2020 as planned in the franchise consultation released on 20 July 2017.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","7515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756036","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Department for Transport sets franchised train operators challenging targets for train punctuality and reliability, which are reinforced in more recent franchises by financial incentive mechanisms. The Department works closely with operators during the course of their franchises to monitor delivery and if necessary to ensure remedial action is taken if performance falls short of plan.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-07T14:00:38.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756036/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756036/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756036/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Railways: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to work with the rail franchises to ensure greater reliability for passengers.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","6978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756037","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The working group on taxi and private hire vehicle licensing, as announced on 5 July 2017, will have its first meeting on 26 September 2017. The group’s membership and terms of reference will be formally confirmed at that meeting, and copies of those documents will subsequently be deposited in the library of the House.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-11T11:14:16.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756037/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756037/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756037/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Taxis: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to his oral statement of 5 July 2017, Official Report, column 153WH, when his Department plans to publish the (a) terms of reference and (b) names of the chair and members of the working party on working conditions in the private hire industry.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","6953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756038","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government is determined to meet its air quality obligations. The Government published the final UK Air Quality Plan on 26 July which includes additional measures to improve air quality nationwide.</p><p> </p><p>The Government consulted on a draft Airports NPS between 2 February and 25 May this year and the consultation document was clear that further work was underway to update the evidence base, including revised aviation demand forecasts and the government’s final Air Quality Plan. The Secretary of State for Transport announced on 7 September that there is a need to conduct a short period of further consultation to allow this updated evidence to be taken into account.</p><p> </p><p>The draft Airports National Policy Statement sets out the Government’s view that, with a suitable package of policy and mitigation measures, the Heathrow Northwest Runway scheme would be capable of being delivered without impacting the UK’s compliance with air quality limit values. The government will make meeting air quality legal requirements a condition of planning approval.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-12T13:05:32.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756038/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756038/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756038/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Airports: Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effect of the absence of an air quality strategy on the draft national policy statement on airports.","false","Biography information for Ruth Cadbury","Brentford and Isleworth","Ruth Cadbury","6960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756039","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-07","<p>My officials have regular discussions with UK airlines and others about flights from Sharm el Sheikh.</p><p> </p><p>My aviation security experts continue to work closely with their Egyptian counterparts on the ground, sharing their expertise in establishing effective security arrangements.</p><p> </p><p>We look forward to achieving the return of flights to Sharm el Sheikh, once we can be assured of there being the necessary secure and sustainable security situation.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-07T15:19:51.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756039/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756039/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756039/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Aviation: Egypt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to lift the ban on flights from the UK to Sharm el-Sheikh, Egypt.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","6992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756040","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-07","<p>My Department carries out regular assessments of aviation security at all last points of departure airports to the UK from Egypt. It is long standing government policy not to comment in detail on security matters. However the Government works closely with international partners, including airlines, airports and the Egyptian Government, on security standards. Global aviation security arrangements are kept under constant review.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-07T15:17:15.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756040/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756040/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756040/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Aviation: Egypt","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of safety on international flights to Sharm el-Sheikh.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","6993"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756041","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Department is still undertaking a process of information gathering to develop the specification for the next East Midlands rail franchise.</p><p> </p><p>All options for future East Midlands services are subject to analysis of the potential benefits and consultation with stakeholders, which is currently ongoing. We are considering the case for additional services to Luton Airport and are working collaboratively with Luton Airport to understand their proposals. Any outcome will seek to secure the best value for money for the taxpayer, be in the best interests of passengers and the decisions will be taken using economic analysis, which includes social and environmental impacts.</p><p> </p><p>The formal public consultation continues until 11 October and will inform the specification, I would strongly encourage the honourable Member to make his views known through the consultation process before it closes.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-12T13:10:07.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756041/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756041/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756041/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Railways: Luton Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the consultation document on East Midlands rail franchise, published in July 2017, whether his Department has considered the effect on the local economy of an increase in the number of fast trains from London to London Luton Airport to four an hour.","false","Biography information for Mr Gavin Shuker","Luton South","Mr Gavin Shuker","6862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756042","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>All options for future East Midlands services are subject to analysis of the potential benefits and consultation with stakeholders, which is currently ongoing. This consultation explicitly raises the issue of services to Luton Airport Parkway.</p><p> </p><p>The formal public consultation continues until 11 October and will inform the future franchise specification.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-11T13:35:58.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756042/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756042/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756042/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Railways: Luton Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether consultation on the East Midlands rail franchise will take into account the volume of air passengers at London Luton Airport; and what assessment he has made of the (a) economic, (b) social and (c) environmental merits of improved rail services related to that franchise to that airport.","false","Biography information for Mr Gavin Shuker","Luton South","Mr Gavin Shuker","6861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756043","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government is committed to improving services on the Uckfield Line. We recently completed a £19.2m project to enable longer 10-car trains to operate on the line, giving passengers much-needed extra seating and space. Further improvements will be further assessed in light of available funding, as part of the development of our infrastructure upgrade plans for Control Period 6, covering 2019–2024.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-12T12:53:09.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756043/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756043/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756043/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Lewes-Uckfield Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will implement the recommendation in Appendix 5 of the Gibb Report on electrification of the Uckfield line.","false","Biography information for Tom Tugendhat","Tonbridge and Malling","Tom Tugendhat","7199"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756044","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Department has established a working group to consider current issues concerns relating to taxi and private hire vehicle licensing, and produce focussed recommendations for action. National standards were proposed by the Law Commission in its 2014 report on taxi and private hire licensing, and I have asked the working group to consider relevant Law Commission recommendations in its deliberations.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-11T11:27:52.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756044/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756044/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756044/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Taxis: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department plans to establish minimum requirements which all local authorities must abide by when granting licenses to taxi or private hire vehicle drivers.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","7183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756045","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government currently has no plans to establish a national database of registered taxi and private hire vehicles. However, at the recent Westminster Hall Debate on the ‘Regulation of working conditions in the private hire industry’ I announced my intention to set up a working group to consider the regulation of the sector. The group’s terms of reference and membership will be confirmed shortly.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-12T16:42:12.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756045/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756045/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756045/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Taxis: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department plans to establish a national database of registered taxi and private hire vehicles in conjunction with the DVLA and police.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","7184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756046","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>Dualling the A1 to Scotland will have to be done in stages to limit disruption. The 13 mile section of the A1 between Morpeth and Ellingham is already being dualled as part of the first Road Investment Strategy. The Department has had Board level discussions with Transport Scotland about improving the remainder of the A1 from Newcastle to Scotland, and will continue to look at the case for dualling the route, taking into account Scotland’s revised Transport Strategy upon its publication.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-11T10:35:08.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756046/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756046/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756046/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","A1: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with the Scottish Government about improvement to the A1.","false","Biography information for John Lamont","Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","John Lamont","7142"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756047","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The vast majority of heavy goods vehicles are required to be fitted with a speed limiter set at 56 miles per hour and this must be used at all times. This is distinct from the road-based speed limits, which for heavy goods vehicles in England and Wales is 50 miles per hour on single carriageways and 60 miles per hour on dual carriageways and motorways. The Government has no current plans to change the speed limiter requirements or the national speed limits for heavy goods vehicles.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-11T10:46:34.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756047/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756047/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756047/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Large Goods Vehicles: Speed Limits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans his Department has to reduce the speed limit for heavy goods vehicles from 56 miles per hour.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","7152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756048","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-12","<p>My Department works closely with the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs in developing the Government’s response to the shared challenges of improving air quality and reducing greenhouse gas emissions. The Government announced an intention to end the sale of all new conventional cars and vans by 2040 as part of the ‘UK plan for tackling roadside nitrogen dioxide concentrations’ (July 2017). My Department engaged closely with the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs and other relevant departments to draft and agree this Plan, including at Ministerial level.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-12T08:25:01.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756048/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756048/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756048/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Motor Vehicles: Fuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions his Department had with the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs before the announcement of a ban on petrol and diesel vehicles by 2040.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","John Spellar","7176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756049","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Department does not hold this information. We have estimates of accident costs in our online appraisal guidance (WebTAG) These estimates include police costs, damage to property and insurance and admin costs. Costs are split between built up roads with a speed limit of 40 mph or less and non-built up roads with speed limits greater than 40mph. Data is not available for A roads specifically.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-11T10:15:56.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756049/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756049/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756049/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Roads: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the average cost is of dealing with a fatal road traffic accident on an A road.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","7084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756050","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The second round of New Stations funding was announced on 28 July and the five new stations are due to be delivered by March 2020 at the latest. The Department will seek further funding in due course for future years.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-11T13:32:29.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756050/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756050/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756050/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Railway Stations: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department will be launching a New Stations Fund 3.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","7109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756051","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-12","<p>To the extent that works are required at York to accommodate the overall number of trains including HS2 in the 2030s, this will be taken into account as part of the normal railway industry planning processes.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-12T07:26:18.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756051/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756051/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756051/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","High Speed 2 Railway Line: York Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what funding will be available to York Railway Station to handle HS2 services.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","7110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756052","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-12","<p>Train service assumptions for HS2 and other rail services at York have been published as part of the HS2 Phase 2 business case. Railway industry planning processes will further develop assessments of capacity and more detailed timetable plans in due course.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-12T08:05:44.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756052/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756052/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756052/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","High Speed 2 Railway Line: York Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of York Railway Station's capacity to handle HS2 services.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","7111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756053","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>We currently have no plans to launch a further round of the Better Bus Area programme.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-11T12:39:00.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756053/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756053/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756053/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Bus Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department will be launching a further Better Bus Area programme.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","7108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756054","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Department for Transport announced on 1<sup>st</sup> August 2017 those local highway authorities who were successful in being awarded funding through Tranche 2a of the local highways maintenance challenge fund.</p><p> </p><p>Further details of the announcement and the schemes receiving funding can be seen at the following weblink:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/councils-share-75-million-for-major-road-improvements" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/councils-share-75-million-for-major-road-improvements</a></p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-11T10:55:33.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756054/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756054/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756054/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Roads: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he will announce successful applications to the Highways Maintenance Challenge Fund 2a.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","7107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756055","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>There are no plans to introduce an age-related extension to the concessionary travel scheme. The age of eligibility for the scheme is currently rising in line with the state pension age. This will address the anomalous position of non-disabled people of working age having access to free bus travel, and will help the financial sustainability of the scheme.</p><p> </p><p>Under concessionary travel legislation, all local authorities in England also have a power to offer additional concessions to their residents, such as free travel for older people who are yet to reach pension age.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-11T09:56:27.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756055/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756055/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756055/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Bus Services: Concessions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will introduce proposals to make available a free bus pass for people at the age of 60.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","7333"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756056","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The £175m Safer Roads Fund targets the 50 local authority 'A' road sections in England that carry the highest risk of death and serious injury to road users, based on analysis by the Road Safety Foundation. The list of the 50 highest risk road sections, published in January 2017, can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/roads-funding-information-pack" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/roads-funding-information-pack</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The sections of the A19 that are the responsibility of local highway authorities do not feature within this top 50 list and so are not eligible for the Safer Roads Fund.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-11T12:45:13.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756056/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756056/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756056/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","A19: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to the Answer of 20 April 2017 to Question 70178, how much of the £175 million allocated to local highways authorities will be spent on improving road safety on the A19.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","7235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756057","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-12","<p>Figures on public sector spend per head of population at a regional level are available as part of the government’s Country and Regional Analysis (CRA) statistics. However, the benefits from this spend on transport interventions will often accrue to motorists or passengers far beyond the residents of the immediate local area or region. This is particularly the case for spending on motorways, trunk roads, and the railway which connect cities and regions across the country. Although the CRA attempts to allocate expenditure on the basis of the regions that benefit from the spend, rather than where it is made, inevitably allocations are not always precise.</p><p> </p><p>The latest CRA statistics (2016) for the North East of England suggest that in 2015-16, total government expenditure on transport per head of population was £182. This information is available for government office regions only, and therefore is unavailable for Northumberland or the Wansbeck constituency.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-12T11:53:26.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756057/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756057/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756057/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Transport: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the capital spend on transport was per head of population in (a) the North East, (b) Northumberland and (c) Wansbeck constituency in the last 12 months for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","7225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756058","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-07","<p>Validated collision data for 2016 is expected to be made available by the Department for Transport on the 28<sup>th</sup> September 2017. Data for 2017 will not be available until June 2018. However, validated data is available for the three year period 1 January 2013 to 31 December 2015 for the A120 Pellens Corner, including the Harwich Road junction and can be broken down as follows:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td rowspan="2"><p><strong> </strong> <strong>Year</strong></p></td><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Severity</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Fatal</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Serious</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Slight</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>5</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>5</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-07T13:44:41.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756058/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756058/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756058/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Roads: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what information his Department holds on the (a) number and (b) nature of road traffic incidents recorded at the junction of Harwich Road and the A120 east of Colchester and at Pellens Corner nearby over the last 12 months; and how many times the ambulance service has been required to attend those incidents.","false","Biography information for Sir Bernard Jenkin","Harwich and North Essex","Mr Bernard Jenkin","7374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756059","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Department for Transport does not hold this level of information.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-09-07T14:04:16.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756059/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756059/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756059/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Northern: Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many Northern Rail trains on the Harrogate line in the last 12 months had two carriages.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","7372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756060","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Government undertook impact assessments regarding Regulation (EC) 261/2004, which covers passengers’ rights in the event of denied boarding, at the point of its initial negotiation, and as part of subsequent efforts to reform the Regulation. Both of these issues were within the scope of that assessment.</p><p> </p><p>To protect consumers, financial penalties on the industry through regulation has provided a deterrent to overbooking.</p><p> </p><p>In addition the Government and the CAA have introduced an Alternative Dispute Resolution (ADR) scheme into the sector, which now covers more than 70% of passengers.</p><p> </p><p>We have also begun the process of developing a new strategy for UK aviation. This strategy will put the consumer back at the heart of our thinking and ensure that the sector is delivering for consumers and the country as a whole.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-07T15:30:29.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756060/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756060/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Aviation: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the (a) effect on passengers and (b) extent of airlines overbooking flights; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Daniel Kawczynski","Shrewsbury and Atcham","Daniel Kawczynski","7378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756061","Wales Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union and I have regular discussions on a range of issues, as do officials from our respective departments.</p><p>There may be specific European programmes in which we might want to participate and if so, it will be reasonable that we make a contribution.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-11T10:27:58.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756061/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756061/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-04","INTERREG Programme: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what representations he has made to the Department for Exiting the European Union on continuation of interreg funding for Wales in partnership with Ireland.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","7156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756062","Wales Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The UK Government is keen to encourage any schemes which help to increase participation rates of children in sport. However this is a devolved issue in Wales and therefore the responsibility of the Welsh Government.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-11T10:29:32.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756062/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756062/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-04","Sports: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport on increasing participation rates of Welsh children in sport.","false","Biography information for Tonia Antoniazzi","Gower","Tonia Antoniazzi","6931"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756063","Wales Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The UK Government is keen to encourage any schemes which will increase the participation rates of children in sport and which may also help to tackle mental health issues. However, both of these matters are devolved and therefore the responsibility of the Welsh Government.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-09-11T10:32:51.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756063/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756063/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-04","Sports: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Health on the adequacy of provision of sport in (a) Gower constituency and (b) Wales to tackle mental health issues in primary school-aged children.","false","Biography information for Tonia Antoniazzi","Gower","Tonia Antoniazzi","6932"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756064","Women and Equalities","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Department for Digital, Culture, Media &amp; Sport is working to raise the profile of women’s sport in the media and encourage more commercial investment into women’s sport. Decisions on content and programming are made independently by broadcasters and editors.</p><p>Since the Olympics in 2012, there has been a notable increase in the coverage of women’s sport on terrestrial television, including the recent UEFA Women’s Euro 2017 broadcast on Channel 4.</p><p> </p><p>The Government Equalities Office is committed to removing the barriers to equality and undertakes a range of work to help women and girls achieve their potential, including in education and the workplace.</p><p>Ministers meet frequently to discuss a number of issues concerning women’s representation.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-09-12T17:06:13.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756064/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756064/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756064/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-09-04","Sports: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, whether she plans to discuss with the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport better representation of women's sport on terrestrial television.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","7318"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756065","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>There will be no disruption to current benefit claimants where the full Universal Credit service rolls out. The service is for new claims or for those who have a significant change in circumstances.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-11T13:19:38.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756065/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756065/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Social Security Benefits: Kingston upon Hull","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to ensure minimal disruption in the regularity in which claimants in Hull will receive income from their benefits prior to the introduction there of universal credit in 2018.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","7316"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756066","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>DWP publishes details of data protection breaches affecting protected personal information in the Department’s Annual Report and Accounts, available on <a href="http://www.gov.uk" target="_blank"><em>www.gov.uk</em></a>. The number of incidents and the page they appear in the DWP Annual Report for each year since 2010 are listed below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>2 (on page 16 of DWP Accounts)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>1 (page 33)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>0 (page 29)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2 (page 30)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2 (page 81)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>0 (page 84)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>0 (page 92)</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-11T13:57:19.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756066/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756066/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756066/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Department for Work and Pensions: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many breaches of data protection there have been in his Department in each year since 2010; and to which parts of his Department's work those breaches relate.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756067","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>DWP conducted some early analysis based on staff home postcodes and pre-existing rail and bus timetables and timings; this was a preliminary exercise when a number of potential sites were under consideration. However, whilst the Department has identified a potential location north of Cardiff for a new strategic hub, it is not yet confirmed. It is therefore too early to determine which existing offices will move to a hub location in the future, or to make further assessment of public transport provision. The site is to be retained as part of the DWP estate for the next 3-5 years.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-11T13:24:35.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756067/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756067/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756067/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Pension Service: Cwmbran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department made of public transport provision for former Cwmbran Pension Centre staff whose posts will be relocated to North Cardiff.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","7286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756068","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Cwmbran Pension Centre site is to be retained as part of the DWP estate for the next 3-5 years, and as such no decision has yet been made on the closure of the site. As a large employer, DWP understands the potential impact that a closure or relocation of an office may have. Generally though the economic impact of employment is dispersed beyond the specific location of a workplace – because people spend most of their money where they live. I would also add that as our estate is made up of leased buildings, the landlords may offer premises to new tenants once DWP vacate.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-11T12:14:05.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756068/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756068/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756068/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Pension Service: Cwmbran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the closure of Cwmbran Pension Centre on local communities.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","7287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756069","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>DWP has worked with the Hidden Impairment National Group (HING) to develop the Hidden Impairment Toolkit, which offers information on how to best support people with Autism.</p><p> </p><p>DWP is an active member of the Autism Programme Board (APB), responsible for the cross-government implementation of the Think Autism strategy. <strong>DWP</strong> also helped to develop a Disability Passport - About Me - to support people with autism who are seeking jobs.</p><p> </p><p>DWP worked with Autism Alliance UK to deliver an Autism training programme, to over 1200 staff members in Jobcentre Plus, and to develop an Autism and Neuro-diversity toolkit which is available across the Civil Service.</p><p> </p><p>Finally, Improving Lives – the Work, Health and Disability Green Paper’ sets out the Government’s proposals for improving work and health outcomes for disabled people and people with long-term health conditions, including people with autism. We are now considering consultation responses and the next steps for longer term reform.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-12T12:23:06.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756069/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756069/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756069/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Employment: Autism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to increase the proportion of people diagnosed with autism who are in full-time or part-time work.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","7308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756070","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Cwmbran Pension Centre site is to be retained as part of the DWP estate for the next 3-5 years, and as such no decision has yet been made on the closure of the site or relocation of staff. However it is worth reiterating that in the future and should the decision be made to relocate jobs, there will be a period of staff consultation where they will be invited to discuss their individual circumstances.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-11T11:54:44.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756070/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756070/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756070/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Pension Service: Cwmbran","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what consultation was undertaken with staff at Cwmbran Pension Centre before the decision to relocate those staff to North Cardiff.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","7285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756071","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>The information requested is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-11T12:52:15.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756071/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756071/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756071/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Social Security Benefits: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many benefits appeals are received by his Department on the basis of correspondence not having been received.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756072","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Office for National Statistics publishes annual data on deaths registered in the UK by single year of age. The latest data available for England and Wales is for 2016, whilst for the UK the latest data available is for 2015, as the 2016 data is provisional. The data tables can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/birthsdeathsandmarriages/deaths/datasets/deathregistrationssummarytablesenglandandwalesdeathsbysingleyearofagetables" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/birthsdeathsandmarriages/deaths/datasets/deathregistrationssummarytablesenglandandwalesdeathsbysingleyearofagetables</a></p><p>In 2015, the state pension age for women increased from around 62 years and 5 months to around 62 years and 10 months. In 2015 the state pension age for men was 65.</p><p>In 2016, the state pension age for women increased from around 62 years and 11 months to around 63 years and 6 months. In 2016 the state pension age for men was 65.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-09-12T09:59:24.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756072/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756072/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756072/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Retirement: Age","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many men and women in the most recent year for which data are available died before they reached state pension age.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","7284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756073","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The number of complaints received and investigated from August 2016 to August 2017 is 3782.</p><p> </p><p>All complaints are investigated. We are unable to attribute the complaints to Region due to limitations of data recording.</p><p> </p><p>DWP contact the customer within 15 working days to tell them of the outcome or when they can expect a response, if it will take longer.</p><p> </p><p>The department does not hold cost figures for such investigations and these complaints are handled within the normal business of the department.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-09-12T16:25:59.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756073/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756073/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756073/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many complaints his Department has (a) received and (b) investigated in the last 12 months in each region from women born in the 1950s and affected by changes in state pension age; what criteria are used to determine whether a complaint is investigated; how many such investigations have been completed; and what the anticipated (i) timescale and (ii) cost is of each such investigation under way.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","7309"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756074","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>We have a number of contracts in place with private sector suppliers for the sorting, processing and delivery of the Department’s correspondence.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-12T16:30:43.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756074/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756074/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756074/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Department for Work and Pensions: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether private sector contractors have any role in the processing of outbound correspondence from his Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","7282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756075","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Statistics are available on the number of individuals in receipt of Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) with a primary disabling condition in the category Mental or Behavioural Disorder who received an adverse sanction decision and these are published on Stat-Xplore here: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to extract the relevant information can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-11T12:23:00.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756075/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756075/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756075/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Social Security Benefits: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many sanctions have been issued to claimants who have a registered mental health illness in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756076","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>Any need for an advance payment or other financial or budgeting support should be established at the outset of a claim for Universal Credit. This includes existing benefit claimants who move to Universal Credit through a change of circumstances. In the initial new claim interview, work coaches are trained to offer personal budgeting support and assess whether claimants need help to manage until their first Universal Credit payment. If so they are advised to apply for an advance. Furthermore, additional work has been done by the Department to raise awareness of advances nationally, including providing options on the UC Helpline, and signposting through the new “Universal Credit &amp; you” guide for claimants and on the new online Money Manager tool offered by the Money Advice Service. We will shortly be publishing data on advances.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","7497 ; 7616 ; 7617 ; 9501","2017-09-11T14:26:31.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756076/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756076/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756076/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Universal Credit: Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to inform current benefit claimants in Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle constituency that they are entitled to an advance payment to switching to universal credit.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","7326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756077","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>We are intending to publish further data on payment timeliness in due course, but our latest internal data nationally, suggests around 80% of cases are paid in full at the end of the first assessment period.</p><p> </p><p>For the remaining cases we estimate around a third have not signed up to their claimant commitment so cannot be paid until they have. The other two thirds have an outstanding verification issue, such as providing bank statements, evidence of childcare costs, or proof of rent. Many of these claimants receive a part-payment where elements of the claim have been verified.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","7328 ; 7431 ; 8923 ; 9191","2017-09-11T12:21:29.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756077/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756077/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756077/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Universal Credit: Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of claimants in Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle constituency who will wait more than 11 weeks to receive any payment from universal credit following its introduction there in 2018.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","7329"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756078","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>We are intending to publish further data on payment timeliness in due course, but our latest internal data nationally, suggests around 80% of cases are paid in full at the end of the first assessment period.</p><p> </p><p>For the remaining cases we estimate around a third have not signed up to their claimant commitment so cannot be paid until they have. The other two thirds have an outstanding verification issue, such as providing bank statements, evidence of childcare costs, or proof of rent. Many of these claimants receive a part-payment where elements of the claim have been verified.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","7329 ; 7431 ; 8923 ; 9191","2017-09-11T12:21:29.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756078/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756078/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756078/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Universal Credit: Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of claimants in Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle constituency who will wait more than six weeks to receive any payment from universal credit following its introduction there in 2018.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","7328"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756079","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Department has not made such an estimate.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-11T12:17:55.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756079/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756079/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756079/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Universal Credit: Kingston upon Hull","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of people in Hull who will claim universal credit when it is introduced there in 2018.","false","Biography information for Emma Hardy","Kingston upon Hull West and Hessle","Emma Hardy","7327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756080","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-07","<p>As of February 2017, there were 6.8 million working age benefit claimants, of whom 480,000 were on Jobseekers Allowance. 150,000 had been claiming JSA for over 12 months.</p><p> </p><p>A further 280,000 people were in the Universal Credit ‘Searching for Work’ group. Information on the duration of Universal Credit claims by conditionality group is not currently available. This also means that it not possible to calculate the overall proportion of claimants who are long-term unemployed.</p><p> </p><p>Published information is not available on (b) and (c).</p><p> </p><p>We will be maintaining services to claimants and will continue to support them with changes in Jobcentre location, taking into account their individual circumstances, including any health conditions, disabilities or caring responsibilities.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-07T15:52:07.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756080/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756080/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756080/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many and what proportion of claimants accessing jobcentre services are (a) long-term unemployed, (b) identified as having additional support needs and (c) identified as having additional employment skills or training needs; what steps his Department has taken to review the needs of long-term unemployed and other claimants with identified needs; and what additional support his Department plans to provide to such claimants as a result of planned jobcentre closures.","false","Biography information for Lesley Laird","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Lesley Laird","7273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756081","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Department believes that the mix of locations and buildings chosen will give us the best opportunity to deliver our Corporate Centre strategy whilst future-proofing our Corporate Centre estate.</p><p> </p><p>The planned Corporate Centre hubs give us an opportunity to provide the right workspace, whilst ensuring that we minimise under-used space and that colleagues aren’t spread across numerous locations. Hubs will be designed to encourage more effective collaborative working between wider teams, along with other work space benefits i.e. areas for small informal meetings, quiet working and group working.</p><p> </p><p>In terms of co-location and sharing premises, we have worked with DWP operational colleagues and Local Authority leaders to identify and progress Jobcentre co-location opportunities which benefit both the taxpayer and customers</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-07T16:07:51.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756081/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756081/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756081/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the effectiveness of regional corporate hubs or shared premises as part of the planned changes to jobcentres.","false","Biography information for Lesley Laird","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Lesley Laird","7274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756082","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-07","<p>Guidelines around the movement of jobcentres, referred to as ‘ministerial criteria’, have been used for many years across the whole of the UK network. They originated from a desire to standardise the circumstances when considering the movement of one jobcentre to another. They do not reflect the travel times for all claimants, many of whom routinely travel much further or longer to reach their nearest jobcentre.</p><p> </p><p>Jobcentre distances and journey times were calculated using a variety of methods to ensure as accurate an assessment as possible, recognising the number of variables that might factor in claimants actual journeys. This included online tools and timetables, information collected on local public transport routes, and input and scrutiny from local DWP colleagues and management. Whilst there is no statutory requirement to do so, DWP opted to carry out a public consultation to seek the views of everyone with an interest in the closure Jobcentres that were outside of the ministerial criteria.</p><p> </p><p>Jobseekers who have been claiming Universal Credit or Jobseeker’s Allowance for more than 13 weeks can apply for a Jobcentre Plus Travel Discount Card, which halves the cost of pay as you go bus fares.</p><p> </p><p>Furthermore, the Flexible Support Fund can, where appropriate, be used to help claimants with travel costs of undertaking various work search activities (for example formal training) or job interviews.</p><p> </p><p>The reimbursement of travel costs is available to claimants when they are required to attend the jobcentre for appointments other than mandatory fortnightly signing appointments. In addition, those claiming Employment and Support Allowance and Income Support are not required to attend their local jobcentre on a regular basis.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-07T16:03:11.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756082/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756082/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756082/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the evidential basis is for the jobcentre services in Scotland meeting the Government's criteria of three miles or 20 minutes radius travel distance for claimants to reach a jobcentre; what modes of transport his Department used in its assessment of travel time; what consultation his Department has carried out with claimants affected by proposed jobcentre closures; and what additional support or funding his Department plans to provide to claimants with additional travel costs.","false","Biography information for Lesley Laird","Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath","Lesley Laird","7275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756083","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>I replied to the hon. Member’s invitation on 7<sup>th</sup> September 2017.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-11T12:47:48.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756083/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756083/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756083/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he plans to respond to the letter of 7 July 2017 from the hon. Member for Glasgow East on the proposed closure of Easterhouse and Parkhead Jobcentres.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756084","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>The fundamental principle behind waiting days is that benefits are not designed to provide cover for brief spells of unemployment or sickness. To ensure we provide a vital safety net for vulnerable people, a number of groups are exempt from waiting days and any need for financial or budgeting support will be established at the outset of the claim.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-11T12:42:59.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756084/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756084/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756084/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons there is a seven-day waiting period for universal credit; and what assessment he has made of the effect of that waiting period on a claimant's wellbeing.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","7269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756085","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>Direct Payment (DP) into a bank, building society, or credit union account is the safest and most cost-effective method used to make customer benefit and pensions payments. DWP is committed to tackling financial exclusion and helping more people to move towards, and benefit from, mainstream banking but we do recognise that some customers remain unable to access or use such services. Arrangements are in place to ensure those customers can access their money.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-12T16:10:04.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756085/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756085/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756085/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Social Security Benefits: Automated Credit Transfer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his Department's policy is on paying benefits to claimants who do not have a bank account.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","7262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756086","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Department has made no such recent assessments.</p><p> </p><p>Assessments of the trends in low income rates for the population and its headline sub-groups are available in DWP’s Households Below Average Income survey:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/households-below-average-income-199495-to-201516" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/households-below-average-income-199495-to-201516</a></p><p> </p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-09-12T10:03:19.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756086/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756086/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756086/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Poverty: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessments have been made of poverty rates among women aged 60 to 62.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","7207"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756087","Department of Health","false","2017-09-12","<p>The number of people detained under the Mental Health Act 1983 with specific conditions is not collected centrally.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-12T14:34:13.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756087/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756087/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756087/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","Compulsorily Detained Psychiatric Patients: Parkinson's Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many people with Parkinson's disease have been sectioned under the Mental Health Act 1983 in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","7143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756088","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions has identified the average length of time that every intervention type is expected to take. This can be between 5 minutes and 120 minutes depending on the circumstances of the individual and which benefit(s) they are claiming. The Work Coach will undertake a variety of interventions throughout the course of the working day, but please note that some of their time is spent on activities that are not directly related to their role, such as staff meetings, computer activity and other administrative tasks.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-11T12:25:28.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756088/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756088/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756088/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average length of time is that a jobcentre work coach has available to spend with each claimant at each appointment.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","7125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756089","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>To answer this question, “repeat assessments” has been interpreted to mean Disability Living Allowance (DLA) to Personal Independence Payment (PIP) reassessments. The table below gives statistics on the number of completed DLA reassessments to PIP by year of DLA reassessment for people with (a) Parkinson's disease, (b) multiple sclerosis, (c) motor neurone disease, (d) rheumatoid arthritis and (e) cystic fibrosis.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1: reassessments for Parkinson’s disease, multiple sclerosis, Motor neurone disease, rheumatoid arthritis and cystic fibrosis by year of reassessment (April 2013 to October 2016)</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Parkinson's disease</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>70</p></td><td><p>420</p></td><td><p>1,490</p></td><td><p>1,980</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Multiple sclerosis</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>490</p></td><td><p>1,950</p></td><td><p>7,710</p></td><td><p>10,160</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Motor neurone disease</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>40</p></td><td><p>130</p></td><td><p>190</p></td><td><p>360</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Rheumatoid arthritis</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1,130</p></td><td><p>3,860</p></td><td><p>9,930</p></td><td><p>14,920</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cystic fibrosis</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>40</p></td><td><p>150</p></td><td><p>460</p></td><td><p>650</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1,170</p></td><td><p>6,510</p></td><td><p>19,800</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>October 2016 is the latest published data available. Later data is available but has been withheld as will be published as part of official statistics in December 2017.</p><p>We recognise that claimants in the ESA Support Group and UC Limited Capability for Work Related Activity with the most severe health conditions or disabilities who have conditions that are unlikely to improve, and are unlikely to ever be able to move closer to the labour market and into work, are having to go through a very lengthy, stressful and bureaucratic process to claim their benefits.</p><p> </p><p>We are working with our assessment provider, medical professionals and other stakeholders, to develop a set of criteria that will help us identify those with the most severe health conditions or disabilities, for whom ESA reassessments can be stopped unless there is a change of circumstances.</p><p> </p><p>Reviews of PIP are a key part of the benefit and ensure that not only awards remain correct where needs may change and that we also maintain contact with the claimant, both features missing from its predecessor Disability Living Allowance. PIP recognises that for the most severely disabled claimants, the award review process could seem unnecessarily intrusive. Existing PIP claimants with the most severe, lifetime disabilities, whose functional ability has remained the same, are more likely to have their evidence reviewed by a DWP Decision-Maker and will not need to have another face-to-face assessment with a healthcare professional.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-12T16:36:41.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756089/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756089/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756089/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Personal Independence Payment: Medical Examinations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many completed repeat assessments there have been of people with (a) Parkinson's disease, (b) multiple sclerosis, (c) motor neurone disease, (d) rheumatoid arthritis and (e) cystic fibrosis, by year of repeat assessment, since the introduction of personal independence payments in 2013; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","7144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756090","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-12T12:43:07.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756090/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756090/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756090/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Social Security Benefits: Chronic Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people with (a) cystic fibrosis, (b) rheumatoid arthritis, (c) motor neurone disease, (d) multiple sclerosis and (e) Parkinson's disease have qualified for (i) income-related employment and support allowance and (ii) income-related jobseeker's allowance since 2008; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","7145"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756091","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>There were 30 female Jobseeker’s Allowance claimants over the age of 60 in the county borough of Bridgend, which includes Porthcawl, as of July 2017.</p><p> </p><p>This information is published by NOMIS and available at <a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/default.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/default.asp</a>&gt; and can be accessed by choosing the Jobseekers Allowance Age and Duration dataset and selecting “local authorities: county / unitary (as of April 2015) (Oct 2004 onwards)”, age, sex and date.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users can be found at <a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp</a>&gt;.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T10:58:53.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756091/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756091/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756091/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobseeker's Allowance: Bridgend and Porthcawl","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many women over the age of 60 claim jobseeker's allowance at (a) Bridgend Jobcentre and (b) Porthcawl Jobcentre; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","7146"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756092","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","7139","2017-09-11T12:30:59.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756092/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756092/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756092/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many universal credit starts since 1 April 2017 were by recipients of employment and support allowance.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","7138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756093","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>Between October 2008 and September 2015 there were fewer than 50 individuals, whose main disabling condition was recorded as Parkinson’s disease, who stopped receiving Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) after twelve months and did not have a completed Work Capability Assessment.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Notes</strong></p><ol><li>An individual may have made more than one ESA claim and had more than one assessment in the time period shown. These individuals will only be counted once.</li><li>The primary medical condition recorded on the claim form does not itself confer entitlement to ESA. So, for example, a decision on entitlement for a customer claiming ESA on the basis of Parkinson’s disease would be based on their ability to carry out the range of activities assessed by the work capability assessment.</li></ol>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-12T12:31:00.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756093/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756093/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756093/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Employment and Support Allowance: Parkinson's Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people with Parkinson's disease have had employment and support allowance cancelled after 12 months without undergoing a work capability assessment; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","7147"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756094","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The responses to complaints received are being handled within normal business activities.</p><p> </p><p>No additional staff have been employed to respond to these complaints.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-09-12T09:57:20.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756094/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756094/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756094/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many (a) staff are deployed to respond to complaints received from women born in the 1950s affected by the change to the state pension age and (b) additional staff have been employed to respond to those complaints in each of the last 12 months; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","7148"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756095","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Department investigate each complaint received.</p><p> </p><p>The first formal complaint relating to women born in the 1950s affected by the changes to the state pension age was received on 16 August 2016.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-09-12T16:06:04.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756095/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756095/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756095/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, on what date his Department opened an investigation into complaints made by women born in the 1950s affected by the changes to the state pension age; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","7149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756096","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>From April 2017, as announced in the Green Paper, <em>Improving Lives</em>, we rolled out the new Personal Support Package (PSP) for people with health conditions. So far we have recruited 300 new Disability Employment Advisers, allocated £15 million to the Flexible Support Fund, made changes to the permitted work rules, and almost completed the roll out of the Health and Work Conversation. This is in line with our ambition to provide a support system which can be tailored to individuals’ needs.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the PSP, we have been rolling out a £330m package from April 2017, delivering a broad range of employment and health support for new ESA Work Related Activity Group and UC Limited Capability for Work claimants. For those claimants, the national employment support provision has been expanded and extended so that there are spaces available on Work Choice and Specialist Employability Support. This will also apply to the Work and Health Programme when it is rolled out from November 2017. We have introduced Community Partners to Jobcentres across Great Britain, peer support Journey to Employment job clubs and deployed trained Small Employer Advisors to deliver the Small Employer Offer.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-12T16:47:45.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756096/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756096/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756096/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Disability: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what progress has been made towards introducing personalised and tailored employment support for disabled people who are looking for work.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","7106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756097","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>Most full time students in higher education do not qualify for Universal Credit. Students, including disabled students and those with health conditions, access fees and living costs support for their higher education courses through various loans and grants funded by the Department for Education.</p><p> </p><p>However, Universal Credit is designed so that a person already in receipt of Universal Credit because of disability or ill health is not discouraged from taking up higher education that may help them in the future.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","7545","2017-09-11T13:08:57.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756097/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756097/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756097/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Disability: Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the introduction of universal credit on the take-up of higher education for full-time disabled students.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","7105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756098","Department for Education","false","2017-09-12","<p>All pupils whose parents are in receipt of universal credit (UC) are currently entitled to free school meals (FSM). This is an interim arrangement during the initial roll-out of UC. The Department for Education is working closely with the Department for Work and Pensions, other Government departments and other interested parties to establish new criteria for determining entitlement to benefits-related FSM as the roll-out progresses. No decision has been taken yet, and our proposals on this matter will be announced in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-09-12T16:11:36.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756098/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756098/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756098/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-04","Universal Credit: Free School Meals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether all families in receipt of universal credit are entitled to free school meals.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","7124"
