e for Education, pursuant to the oral Answer of the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Work and Pensions of 6 July 2017, Official Report, column 1297, on the number of people over 60-years old who started apprenticeships, how many of those people were (a) men and (b) women.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","7386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756149","Department for Education","false","2017-09-12","<p>Apprenticeships offer a route into skilled employment for people of all ages and backgrounds. This could include a young person starting out in their first job, an existing employee up-skilling, or a more experienced worker re-training or re-entering the workforce.</p><p>We are implementing apprenticeship reforms to continue to improve the quality of apprenticeships for all, providing the skills that employers need to reach our commitment of 3 million starts in England by 2020.</p><p>We regularly communicate the benefits of apprenticeships and prospective apprentices can use Find an Apprenticeship to search and apply for apprenticeship vacancies in England. Further information can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/apply-apprenticeship" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/apply-apprenticeship</a>.</p><p>Our Diversity Champions Network is championing gender representation in apprenticeships amongst employers in industries where improvement is needed.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-09-12T14:46:43.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756149/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756149/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756149/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-04","Apprentices: Older Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the oral Answer of the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Work and Pensions of 6 July 2017, Official Report, column 1297, on the number of people over 60-years old who started apprenticeships, what steps her Department is taking to promote apprenticeships for women over 59-years old.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","7387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756150","Department for Education","false","2017-09-12","<p>The department has made estimates of the overall numbers of apprenticeships in future years but does not have a breakdown either by gender or by age.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-09-12T14:51:46.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756150/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756150/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756150/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-04","Apprentices: Older Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Work and Pensions of 5 July 2017, Official Report, column 143WH, on apprenticeships opportunities, how many women over 59-years old her Department estimates will start apprenticeships in each year to 2020-21.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","7388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756151","Department for Education","false","2017-09-12","<p>The table below shows apprenticeship starts by gender for learners aged 60 and over for the available academic years (2011/12 to 2015/16).</p><p> </p><p>Data for the 2016/17 academic year shows starts covering the year reported to date - August 2016 to April 2017.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016/2017</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Full year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Full year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Full year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Full year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Full year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Reported to date</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Female</p></td><td><p>1,650</p></td><td><p>1,520</p></td><td><p>1,170</p></td><td><p>1,690</p></td><td><p>1,780</p></td><td><p>1,780</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Male</p></td><td><p>2,030</p></td><td><p>1,740</p></td><td><p>1,320</p></td><td><p>1,730</p></td><td><p>1,780</p></td><td><p>1,640</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3,680</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3,260</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2,480</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3,410</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3,560</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>3,420</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>Figures rounded and may not add up to totals</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","7386","2017-09-12T14:31:56.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756151/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756151/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756151/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-04","Apprentices: Older Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Work and Pensions of 5 July 2017, Official Report, column 143WH, on apprenticeships opportunities, how many women over 59-years started apprenticeships in each year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","7389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756152","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The upper age limit for Personal Independence Payment (PIP)is age 65 or State Pension age if higher. This is designed to ensure that support is targeted to those who have faced barriers during their working life which they take into older age. This is important as they may have been less able to financially prepare for their retirement. This upper age limit mirrors the current rules in Disability Living Allowance (DLA) which also has a universal upper age limit of 65.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-12T12:50:55.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756152/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756152/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756152/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, on what evidence the decision was taken by his Department to mandate the migration of 65 to 69 year-olds from disability living allowance to personal independence payment.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","7356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756153","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>At 30 April 2017 the number of individuals aged 65-69 who previously received DLA and have been re-assessed as a PIP case was 88,920.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-12T13:44:23.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756153/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756153/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756153/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people aged 65 to 69 have been moved from disability living allowance to personal independence payment.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","7357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756154","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>When PIP was first introduced, the Government worked with Motability to design an extensive Transitional Support package to support Motability customers who were not awarded the enhanced mobility component on reassessment from DLA to PIP. This gives significant help, including up to £2,000 lump or a lease extension for 6 months, the option to buy their old scheme vehicle, and can obtain help to adapt any new, non-scheme vehicle.</p><p> </p><p>More people between the age of 60-64 have had successful reassessment claims for PIP than any other age group. The following link shows the full reassessment results here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-october-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-october-2016</a></p><p> </p><p>Table 8c has the analysis by age:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/576641/pip-official-statistics-dla-to-pip-reassessment-outcomes-october-2016.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/576641/pip-official-statistics-dla-to-pip-reassessment-outcomes-october-2016.ods</a></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-12T14:21:57.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756154/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756154/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756154/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential financial effect on people aged between 65 and 69 who, when mandated to migrate from disability living allowance to personal independence payment, may lose entitlement to mobility elements due to the different criteria of those benefits.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","7362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756155","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-07","<p>There are no are plans to introduce a new duty on energy companies to set out a timetable to reduce the number of households paying for their energy by prepayment meter.</p><p>While data published by Ofgem in its Domestic Suppliers’ Social Obligations annual reports showed prepayment meters have historically been installed to repay debt, the latest report published last year, showed that in 2015 there was evidence of increasing consumer demand for prepayment meters.</p><p>This demand appears to be driven by smart meters operating in pay-as-you-go mode, which are transforming consumer experience of pre-payment metering. Topping up a smart meter in pay-as-you-go mode is as easy as topping up a mobile phone, with no need to access the meter. Being able to see an account balance on an easily accessible In Home Display reduces the risk of pre-payment customers accidently self-disconnecting from their energy supply when they run out of credit. This Government is committed to ensuring every home and small business in the country is offered a smart meter by the end of 2020.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-07T15:41:15.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756155/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756155/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756155/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Energy: Pre-payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he plans to introduce a new duty on energy companies to set out a timetable to reduce the number of people on prepayment meters.","false","Biography information for Patricia Gibson","North Ayrshire and Arran","Patricia Gibson","7400"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756156","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-13","<p>We recognise that low income families with children represent a significant proportion of households in fuel poverty. That is why the Broader Group of Warm Home Discount recipients is focused on working age households, including those with children. The Digital Economy Act will provide Government with the opportunity to help obligated energy suppliers to better target fuel poor households through data matching, including low income families.</p><p>The Act received Royal Assent on 27 April 2017. The Regulations which will commence those powers are expected to come into force in spring 2018. It is the Department’s intention to consult on the future of the Warm Home Discount in 2018 and that the consultation will cover eligibility.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-13T14:15:04.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756156/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756156/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756156/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Warm Home Discount Scheme: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he has made an assessment of the potential merits of including low-income families with young children in the core group of those eligible for the Warm Home Discount.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","7489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756157","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-07","<p>Over the past year, I have held four meetings with representatives of social care providers as well as representatives of care workers. Departmental officials have also had a number of meetings with representatives of both care providers and workers.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-07T15:38:18.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756157/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756157/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756157/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Social Services: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many meetings his Department has had with representatives of the care sector on the payment of sleep-in shifts for care workers.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","7452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756158","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-07","<p>There are no plans at this stage to publish a position paper on the future of the Competition and Markets Authority and its role in investigating multinational mergers after the UK leaves the EU.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-07T14:08:35.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756158/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756158/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756158/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Competition and Markets Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will publish a position paper on the future of the Competition and Markets Authority and its role in investigating multinational mergers after the UK leaves the EU; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","7456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756159","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-08","<p>We have regular discussions with BMW and more generally the Government is working with UK based car manufacturers to increase the level of local content in UK built vehicles.</p><p>Automotive Council research published in June 2017, showed that in value terms, the content sourced by UK car manufacturers increased from 36% in 2011, to 44% in 2017.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","7524","2017-09-08T13:15:08.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756159/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756159/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756159/answer","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756159/answer/previousversion/8975","Biography information for Claire Perry","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","BMW: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what information his Department holds on how much British steel will be used by BMW to manufacture the e-Mini at Cowley.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","7522"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756160","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-08","<p>We have regular discussions with BMW and more generally the Government is working with UK based car manufacturers to increase the level of local content in UK built vehicles.</p><p>Automotive Council research published in June 2017, showed that in value terms, the content sourced by UK car manufacturers increased from 36% in 2011, to 44% in 2017.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry","7522","2017-09-08T13:15:08.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756160/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756160/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756160/answer","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756160/answer/previousversion/8977","Biography information for Claire Perry","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","BMW: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what representations he has made to BMW on the use of British steel to construct the e-Mini at Cowley.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","7524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756161","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Department does not hold information on of the total revenue generated from the investment by small businesses in the life sciences sector in research and development for 2016-17.</p><p>At over 5,000 companies, small businesses comprise 93% of the life sciences sector. The Government recognises the importance of small businesses operating in the sector and the valuable contribution that they make.</p><p>To avoid overburdening businesses there is no mandate for companies to submit information about investments they make in R&amp;D. In many instances it would be difficult to quantify the revenue directly attributable to R&amp;D undertaken rather than by other business activities. Also due to the long timescales involved in R&amp;D any revenue generated by R&amp;D would be generated in a different year from when the R&amp;D was performed.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-09-11T16:00:24.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756161/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756161/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756161/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Life Sciences: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate his Department has made of the total revenue generated from the investment by small businesses in the life sciences sector in research and development for 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Jo Churchill","Bury St Edmunds","Jo Churchill","7501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756162","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Secretary of State attended the Royal Highland Show on 22 June where he held discussions with Scottish Government Ministers and stakeholders including the Scotch Whisky Association. A ministerial meeting is also scheduled to take place in late September.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-12T15:00:09.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756162/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756162/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756162/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-04","Whisky: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions he has had with the Scottish Government about protecting the Scotch whisky industry when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756163","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-08","<p>Work on the Future Capabilities of the UK Steel Sector study is currently ongoing in consultation with the steel industry, and the final report is not yet complete. The Department will look to publish the findings once the work has concluded.</p><p>Government has continued to work closely with the sector, the unions and devolved administrations during the summer to support the UK steel sector develop a long-term viable solution for the UK steel industry.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-09-08T13:59:08.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756163/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756163/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756163/answer","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756163/answer/previousversion/8967","Biography information for Claire Perry","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he plans to publish his Department's paper, Future Capabilities of the UK Steel Sector.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","7012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756164","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-07","<p>We have committed over £67 million to support broadband delivery in Wales. According to Thinkbroadband, in 2012 only 42% of premises in Gower could access superfast speeds. Currently, over 93% of premises in the constituency have this access, with an estimated 3% added so far in 2017.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-07T16:39:55.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756164/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756164/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756164/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Broadband: Gower","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent steps she has taken to improve broadband coverage in Gower constituency.","false","Biography information for Tonia Antoniazzi","Gower","Tonia Antoniazzi","6970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756165","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-09-12","<p>Ensuring that the UK's digital and technology sector remains strong and at the forefront of international innovation and enterprise are priorities for this Government</p><p> </p><p>Since the 2016 referendum, Her Majesty's Government has carried out extensive and diverse engagement with hundreds of businesses of all sizes across the UK on the potential implications of our withdrawal from the EU, alongside extensive wider analysis and engagement.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-09-12T16:55:01.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756165/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756165/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756165/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-09-04","Technology: UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether her Department has undertaken an impact assessment of the effect on the UK tech sector of the UK leaving the single market.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","6873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756166","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Department is in the process of analysing the responses to the Call for Evidence to extend the Groceries Code Adjudicator remit. We will publish the outcome to the Call for Evidence, jointly with Defra, in the autumn.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-11T13:25:08.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756166/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756166/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756166/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Groceries Code Adjudicator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of extending the remit of the Groceries Code Adjudicator to cover support for small businesses and farmers that supply supermarkets.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","6863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756167","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-11","<p>We are planning to publish the Government response to the Call for Evidence on extending the Groceries Code Adjudicator’s remit in the autumn.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-11T13:19:53.3Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756167/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756167/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756167/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Groceries Code Adjudicator","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when his Department plans to publish its response to its call for evidence on extending the remit of the Groceries Code Adjudicator.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","6864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756168","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-12","<p>There are regular discussions between Ministers about how leaving the EU affects UK industries.</p><p>Scotch Whisky is already protected in over 80 countries mostly through registration with Geographical Indication schemes but also through Trade Marks and free trade and other agreements drawn up over many years. Global exports of Scotch were worth £4 billion in 2016. Government is committed to building on this market access and ensuring protection continues after we leave the EU.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-12T15:07:33.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756168/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756168/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756168/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-04","Whisky: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions he has had with Cabinet colleagues about protecting the Scotch whisky industry when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756169","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-08","<p>This is an important plan for the future. It is essential that we take the time to get it right. We are working to ensure that our Clean Growth Strategy is ambitious and robust, and will publish it shortly.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-09-08T13:18:19.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756169/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756169/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756169/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Economic Growth: Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he will publish the Green Growth Plan.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","7070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756170","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Government will set out further detail on its policy for carbon capture and storage (CCS) in the Clean Growth Strategy, which will be published shortly.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-09-07T15:40:54.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756170/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756170/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756170/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the Government's policy is for carbon capture and storage.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","7071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756171","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-08","<p>The Department works closely with the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs in developing the Government’s response to the shared challenges of improving air quality and reducing greenhouse gas emissions. The Government announced an intention to end the sale of all new conventional cars and vans by 2040 as part of the ‘UK plan for tackling roadside nitrogen dioxide concentrations’ (July 2017). The Department engaged closely with the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, the Department for Transport and other relevant departments to draft and agree this plan, including at ministerial level.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-09-08T12:47:16.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756171/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756171/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756171/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Motor Vehicles: Fuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions his Department had with the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs before the announcement of a ban on petrol and diesel vehicles by 2040.","false","Biography information for John Spellar","Warley","John Spellar","7175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756172","Department for Education","false","2017-09-09","<p>Tackling social mobility is at the heart of the government’s ambition to make Britain a country that works for everyone.</p><p>We recognise that where you are born, and the circumstances into which you are born, can still too often determine where you get to in life. In some parts of the country, there is entrenched disadvantage, with less access to good school places or employment opportunities. This can act as barriers to social mobility.</p><p>But we are not prepared to accept Britain as it has been. That is why last year we launched our £72 million Opportunity Areas programme, which brings together local businesses, schools and councils in 12 social mobility ‘coldspots’ across the country to create better opportunities for the children, young people and adults who live there, and to learn lessons about what works in these areas.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","6889","2017-09-09T11:36:25.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756172/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756172/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756172/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-09-04","Social Mobility","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to page 38 of the Social Mobility Commission Report, Time for Change: an assessment of government policies on social mobility 1997-2017, what assessment she has made of the effect of (a) economic and (b) geographic isolation on social mobility.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","7216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756173","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Government believes that widespread free access to cash remains extremely important to the day-to-day lives of many consumers and businesses in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has made no assessment of the effect of closure of ATMs on rural economies and communities, but is monitoring developments within the UK’s ATM network – LINK - as is the Payment Systems Regulator.</p><p> </p><p>The number of ATMs has increased from 36,000 in 2001 to over 70,000 in 2016. LINK also runs a financial inclusion programme which subsidises free to use ATMs in areas without existing access. LINK has identified 1,700 rural and/or deprived ‘target’ areas, and the majority of these areas are now served by 1,110 ATMs, up from 171 in 2007.</p><p> </p><p>The Government regularly engages with industry on access to payment services.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-07T16:47:11.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756173/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756173/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756173/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Cash Dispensing: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment the Government has made of the effect of closure of ATMs in rural areas on the economies and communities of those areas.","false","Biography information for Jamie Stone","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Jamie Stone","7371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756174","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-07","<p>As part of the Industrial Strategy Government we are supporting sectors across the economy to grow, invest and reach their potential. Our new approach challenges sectors to upgrade through “Sector Deals” - an ‘open door’ challenge to industry to come to us with proposals to transform their sector.</p><p> </p><p>In June 2017 my rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State wrote to the CEO of the Scotch Whisky Association welcoming their intention to develop proposals for a sector deal for the Scotch Whisky sector. We look forward to working closely with the sector.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-07T14:13:41.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756174/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756174/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756174/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Whisky: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of providing the Scotch whisky industry with a sectoral deal to promote its competitiveness and growth.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756175","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-12","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply given to the hon. Member for Bridgend, Madeleine Moon, on 26 July 2017, PQ UIN 5521.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-12T12:18:46.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756175/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756175/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756175/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-04","Ivory","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to prevent the trade of ivory.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","7195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756176","Department for International Trade","false","2017-09-12","<p>DIT Ministers and officials engage with the Devolved Administrations in a variety of ways, including having given evidence to the Scottish Parliament’s Culture, Tourism, Europe and External Relations Committee.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-09-12T16:43:11.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756176/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756176/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756176/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-04","Department for International Trade: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, when he last met his counterpart at the (a) National Assembly for Wales and (b) Scottish Parliament; and if he will publish the agenda of those meetings.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","7154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756177","Department for International Trade","false","2017-09-12","<p>The UK Government is committed to seeking continuity in its current trade and investment relationships, including those covered by EU free trade agreements or other EU preferential arrangements. At the UK-Korea JETCO in December 2016, my Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade and the South Korean Trade Minister agreed to establish a UK Korea Trade Working Group. The Working Group will discuss tackling barriers to trade and investment, wider global trade issues and how to ensure continuity for businesses, as well as exploring future trade opportunities following the UK’s exit from the EU. The first meeting of the Working Group was held in Seoul in February 2017.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","7062","2017-09-12T14:38:57.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756177/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756177/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756177/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-04","Trade Agreements: South Korea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what representations have been received from the Government of South Korea on replicating its EU-wide trade deal with the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756178","Department for International Trade","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government is committed to seeking continuity in its current trade and investment relationships, including the CARIFORUM-EU Economic Partnership Agreement which includes the Dominican Republic. My noble Friend, the former Minister of State for Trade Policy (Lord Price), and UK trade officials met with representatives of the CARIFORUM Member States, including the Dominican Republic, in the spring to begin discussions to achieve this.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","7065","2017-09-12T15:41:31.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756178/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756178/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756178/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-04","Trade Agreements: Dominican Republic","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what representations have been made to the Government of the Dominican Republic on replicating its EU-wide trade deal with the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756179","Department for International Trade","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government is committed to seeking continuity in its current trade and investment relationships, including the CARIFORUM-EU Economic Partnership Agreement which includes the Dominican Republic. My noble Friend, the former Minister of State for Trade Policy (Lord Price), and UK trade officials met with representatives of the CARIFORUM Member States, including the Dominican Republic, in the spring to begin discussions to achieve this.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","7064","2017-09-12T15:41:32.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756179/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756179/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756179/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-04","Trade Agreements: Dominican Republic","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what representations he has received from the the Government of the Dominican Republic on replicating its EU-wide trade deal with the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756180","Department for International Trade","false","2017-09-12","<p>The UK Government is committed to seeking continuity in its current trade and investment relationships, including those covered by EU Free Trade Agreements or other EU preferential arrangements. We are actively exploring what may be possible in terms of replicating the effects of the current association agreement with Morocco in order to provide certainty for businesses.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","7067","2017-09-12T14:59:17.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756180/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756180/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756180/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-04","Trade Agreements: Morocco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what representations have been made to the Government of Morocco on replicating its EU-wide trade deal with the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756181","Department for International Trade","false","2017-09-12","<p>The UK Government is committed to seeking continuity in its current trade and investment relationships, including those covered by EU Free Trade Agreements or other EU preferential arrangements. We are actively exploring what may be possible in terms of replicating the effects of the current association agreement with Morocco in order to provide certainty for businesses.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","7066","2017-09-12T14:59:17.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756181/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756181/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756181/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-04","Trade Agreements: Morocco","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what representations he has received from the Government of Morocco on replicating its EU-wide trade deal with the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756182","Department for International Trade","false","2017-09-12","<p>The UK Government will look to ensure continuity of trade between the UK and Turkey, following the UK's exit from the EU, factoring in the possible implications of Turkey's existing customs arrangement with the EU. As a result, officials in the Department for International Trade, the Department for Exiting the EU, the UK Permanent Representation to the EU, and the Foreign and Commonwealth Office have met officials from the Republic of Turkey.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-09-12T14:50:16.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756182/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756182/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756182/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-04","EU External Trade: Turkey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what recent discussions he or officials of his Department have had with the Turkish Government about that country's customs agreement with the EU.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","7099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756183","Department for International Trade","false","2017-09-12","<p>The UK Government is committed to seeking continuity in its current trade and investment relationships, including those covered by EU free trade agreements or other EU preferential arrangements. At the UK-Korea JETCO in December 2016, my Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade and the South Korean Trade Minister agreed to establish a UK Korea Trade Working Group. The Working Group will discuss tackling barriers to trade and investment, wider global trade issues and how to ensure continuity for businesses, as well as exploring future trade opportunities following the UK’s exit from the EU. The first meeting of the Working Group was held in Seoul in February 2017.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","7063","2017-09-12T14:38:57.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756183/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756183/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756183/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-09-04","Trade Agreements: South Korea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what representations have been made to the Government of South Korea on replicating its EU-wide trade deal with the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756185","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-15","<p>There will be no change to the rights and status of EU nationals living in the UK, nor UK nationals living in the EU, while the UK remains in the EU. This means there will be no change to the ability of EU nationals to access services as they do now whilst the UK is an EU member state.</p><p>Our clear intention during negotiations is to ensure that EU citizens living in the UK before the specified date will continue to enjoy access to public services after we leave the EU.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-09-15T13:22:17.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756185/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756185/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756185/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-04","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether he has received evidence of EU nationals facing discrimination in access to services in the UK as a result of the lack of clarity on their future legal status; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","6869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756186","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-13","<p>The UK Government will look to ensure continuity of trade between the UK and Turkey, following the UK's exit from the EU, factoring in the possible implications of Turkey's existing customs arrangement with the EU. UK Officials in the Department for International Trade, the Department for Exiting the EU, the UK Permanent Representation to the EU, and the Foreign and Commonwealth Office have met Officials of the Republic of Turkey who, in the process, have brought up the issue of their own customs arrangements with the EU.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-09-13T13:49:45.713Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756186/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756186/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756186/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-04","EU External Trade: Turkey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what recent discussions he or his officials have had with the Turkish Government about that country's customs agreement with the EU.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","7098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756187","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2017-09-29","<p>The Government will guarantee EU Structural and Investment fund projects signed before we leave the EU, even where these continue after we leave. Beyond these priorities, decisions on the replacement of EU funding will be taken in light of wider UK strategic priorities and other domestic spending decisions. As we transition to longer-term arrangements, we will ensure the devolved administrations are treated fairly and their circumstances are taken into account. The Government is committed to securing a deal that works for the entire United Kingdom - for Scotland, Wales, Northern Ireland and all parts of England.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-09-29T08:25:11.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756187/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756187/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756187/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2017-09-04","INTERREG Programme: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with the Irish Government on the continuation of interreg funding for Wales.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","7155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756188","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-12","<p>The longer term options for subsidy control after we leave the EU are being considered carefully. We will continue to engage with the devolved administrations as we seek a deal that secures the specific interests of Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland, as well as all parts of England.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-09-12T16:06:40.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756188/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756188/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756188/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-04","Assisted Areas: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with the Welsh Government on the future map of assisted areas in Wales.","false","Biography information for Hywel Williams","Arfon","Hywel Williams","7153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756189","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-12","<p>As part of our preparations to leave the EU, we will consider future global trading relationships and the impacts on the food and drink industry. Our ambition is for the UK to become a truly global trading nation and there are great opportunities for Scotland's most celebrated exports, such as Scotch Whisky, to take advantage of the growing interest in British food and drink around the world.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-12T13:28:15.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756189/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756189/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756189/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-04","Whisky: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how the Government plans to negotiate a deal with the EU which has the flexibility required to ensure that the Scotch whisky industry's interests are protected in line with any future changes in market conditions.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756190","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-12","<p>Countries outside the EU are already able to participate in the EU's Protected Food Name schemes when selling onto the EU market. In addition, the rules that currently govern the enforcement of Protected Food Names will be placed on a UK legal basis through the EU Withdrawal Bill. Whether the UK continues to protect EU Protected Food Names from other member states in the UK market will be a matter for negotiation. Some of the Geographical Indicator designations that the UK has, for instance protecting Scotch Whisky in the US, are governed by agreements outside the EU Protected Food Name scheme. The UK will continue to abide by WTO rules on the protection of Geographical Indicators globally.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-12T13:20:21.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756190/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756190/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756190/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-04","Food: Origin Marking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to establish EU respect for future UK geographical indicators after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756191","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-12","<p>Countries outside the EU are already able to participate in the EU's Protected Food Name schemes when selling onto the EU market. In addition, the rules that currently govern the enforcement of Protected Food Names will be placed on a UK legal basis through the EU Withdrawal Bill. Whether the UK continues to protect EU Protected Food Names from other member states in the UK market will be a matter for negotiation. Some of the Geographical Indicator designations that the UK has, for instance protecting Scotch Whisky in the US, are governed by agreements outside the EU Protected Food Name scheme. The UK will continue to abide by WTO rules on the protection of Geographical Indicators globally.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-12T13:21:00.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756191/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756191/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756191/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-04","Food: Origin Marking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether the Government plans to accept and help enforce future EU geographical indicators.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756192","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-13","<p>Ministers have engaged with elected leaders and officials from local councils across the UK and intend to continue this work throughout the exit process. The Department for Exiting the European Union and the Department for Communities and Local Government are working closely with the Local Government Association and regional partners to understand issues related to exit and identify any regional implications.</p><p>The former Minister of State (David Jones, the Rt Hon Member for Clwyd West) held a meeting of the Local Government Associations for England, Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland in February 2017. Further engagement with local government stakeholders is planned in the coming weeks.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-09-13T09:59:45.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756192/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756192/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756192/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-04","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what steps his Department has taken to ensure that the views of town councils and rural and urban district councils are taken into account as the UK defines its stance for negotiation with the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756193","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-13","<p>As part of the deep and special partnership the UK seeks with the EU, we want to continue to work closely with our European Partners, including on security, foreign and defence policy. <br> <br>We want a partnership whereby we contribute to the security of Europe using our range of defence and security capabilities, our networks and influence, our policy expertise and through information sharing.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-09-13T17:05:07.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756193/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756193/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756193/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-04","Arms Trade: Export Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will seek in negotiations with the EU to ensure that the UK continues to participate in EU information exchange and co-operation mechanisms relating to arms and dual-use transfer control.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756194","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-13","<p>As part of the deep and special partnership the UK seeks with the EU, we want to continue to work closely with our European Partners, including on security, foreign and defence policy.</p><p>We want a partnership whereby we contribute to the security of Europe, using our range of defence and security capabilities, our networks and influence and our policy expertise.</p><p>Constraining weapons proliferation is a key foreign policy objective and intelligence and information sharing are central to efforts to identify, interdict and prosecute cases of illicit arms trafficking. Sharing information on interdictions once the UK has left the EU will take place within the broader context of negotiations.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-09-13T17:06:27.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756194/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756194/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756194/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-04","Weapons: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will seek in negotiations with the EU to ensure that the UK continues to co-operate with the EU on issues relating to intelligence and information sharing to maximise efforts to identify, interdict and prosecute cases of illicit arms trafficking.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","7312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756195","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-12","<p>Ministers and officials from across the Government are speaking with a variety of stakeholders from all sectors, including start-ups in the technology sector, to understand business concerns and priorities after EU exit. These discussions will inform our negotiating position.</p><p>Details of Ministerial meetings are published in the Department’s Quarterly Transparency Returns, which are made publicly available on GOV.UK.</p><p>UK projects that are in the process of securing finance from the European Investment Bank (EIB), and its subsidiary the European Investment Fund (EIF), have been affected as the EIB Group undertakes due diligence.</p><p>The Chancellor and senior Treasury officials have been working very closely with EIB Group management to resolve these issues. The UK believes that UK firms should be able to access EIB and EIF funding on equal terms as other Member States while the UK remains a member of the EU, as the Chancellor set out in his Mansion House Speech.</p><p>The government has put in place measures to ensure that UK firms which may no longer be able to access EIB Group finance receive the investment they need. The UK Guarantees Scheme will continue to support UK infrastructure investment and will, for the first time, offer guarantees for the construction phase of a project. The British Business Bank has also been authorised to raise the limit on its investment in individual projects from 33% to 50% and the government will bring forward planned investments in venture capital that were previously announced in the 2016 Autumn Statement.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-09-12T16:05:39.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756195/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756195/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756195/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-04","Technology: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with British start-up technology companies on access to the European Investment Fund and other future funding arrangements for the sector after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756196","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union (DExEU) has paid a total of £2,874,304.63 to the Government Legal Department (GLD) as of 31 August 2017 since the formation of the Department. The Department currently has a fixed fee agreement with the GLD of £3.7m per annum for the provision of approximately 40 (full time equivalent) staff who are providing dedicated legal services to DExEU. The department regularly reviews the level of resource required for all activities including legal advice.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-09-07T16:21:08.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756196/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756196/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756196/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-04","Department for Exiting the European Union: Legal Opinion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to the Answer of 5 September 2016 to Question 43742, how much his Department (a) has spent on legal advice to date and (b) forecasts will be spent on legal advice up to March 2019.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","7210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756197","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-13","<p>This government recognises the value of the UK creative industries, with creative sector growth rising faster than the wider economy and creative exports in strong demand across the world. The UK is home to exceptional creative talent and is global centre of excellence in many areas, including fashion, design and film.</p><p>We want this success to continue. As we enter negotiations with the EU we want to ensure that we get the best deal that works for all sectors, including our vibrant creative industries. Our intention is to secure the freest trade possible in services, including in the creative industries to encourage further growth and to ensure the security of the businesses and skills in the UK.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-09-13T13:45:10.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756197/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756197/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756197/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-04","Arts: Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether he plans to prioritise the creative industries in trade agreement negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","7542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756198","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-09-12","<p>Until the point of exit, the UK remains a full member of the European Union, its institutions and related bodies.</p><p>We want to achieve a deep and special partnership between the UK and the European Union, but the precise nature of this future relationship is a matter for the negotiations.</p><p>It would not be appropriate to publish information which might undermine our negotiating position – a principle that was overwhelmingly supported by the House of Commons in October last year.</p><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-09-12T16:04:24.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756198/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756198/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756198/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-09-04","EU Institutions: Cost Benefit Analysis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, of which EU institutions and other EU-related bodies the UK is a member; and what assessment the Government has made of the financial cost and benefit to the UK of membership of those institutions and bodies.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","7479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756199","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2017-09-13","<p>The Prime Minister has been clear that we want to secure the rights of EU citizens in the UK and UK citizens in the EU as early as possible. We are seeking a reciprocal agreement with the EU to safeguard the rights of UK citizens, and it will be for the EU and its Member States to decide how they will implement any agreed deal.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-09-13T13:48:49.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756199/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756199/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756199/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2017-09-04","EU Citizenship","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will make an assessment of the merits of an opt-in system of payment for UK citizens who want to retain their EU rights.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","7403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756200","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Government has commissioned Dame Judith Hackitt to carry out an Independent Review of Building Regulations and fire safety. We will make work undertaken on Approved Document B before the Grenfell Tower fire, including research, available to Dame Judith as well as to the public inquiry.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-07T16:36:27.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756200/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756200/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756200/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Building Regulations: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to the Answer of 28 July 2017 to Question 2714, if he will publish research or work commissioned before the Grenfell Tower fire in preparation for the revision of Approved Document B of the Building Regulations.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","8326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756201","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-13","<p>Later this month the National Fire Chiefs Council (NFCC) are coordinating a visit from Major General Matrooshi, the Commander in Chief of the UAE Civil Defence in Dubai who has responsibility for fire safety, to discuss approaches to fire safety in Dubai and exchange best practice. This visit will be attended by officials from a number of Departments, including the Home Office and DCLG.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-13T16:12:36.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756201/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756201/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756201/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","High Rise Flats: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in Dubai on the fire at 34 Tamweel Tower, Jumeirah Lakes, Dubai, in 2012.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","8256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756202","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-21","<p>I met with the former Premier of Victoria, the Hon. Ted Baillieu, on 22 August 2017. We discussed the fires that took place in high-rise buildings in and around Victoria in 2014. Mr Baillieu is now is leading a taskforce which has been established to investigate non-compliant cladding in Australia. We agreed to share learning from both the UK and Australian experiences.</p><p>Mr Baillieu has met Dame Judith Hackitt and he will be engaging with her Independent Review. Furthermore, my officials are in dialogue with the Australian Building Codes Board.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-21T11:26:13.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756202/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756202/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","High Rise Flats: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with his counterparts in Australia on the Lacrose Tower fire in 2014.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","8255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756203","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-25","<p>I have not spoken with my French counterpart relating to the Mermoz Tower fire. However, my officials are engaged in work gathering international comparisons as part of our Building Safety Programme.</p><p>In reaching its conclusions, the Independent Review led by Dame Judith Hackitt, will draw upon international experience of regulatory frameworks.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-25T11:13:16.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756203/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756203/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","High Rise Flats: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions he has had with his French counterparts on the Mermoz Tower fire in Roubaix in 2012.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","8254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756204","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The legislation that provides for the licensing of taxi services is enabling in its nature, giving licensing authorities the discretion to set standards that they deem to be appropriate for their area. Although currently there is no requirement in legislation for local authorities to have a published taxi licensing policy in place, the Department for Transport does publish Best Practice Guidance to assist licensing authorities when setting standards for taxi and private hire vehicle (PHV) drivers and operators.</p><p> </p><p>The Department will, for the first time, issue statutory guidance to licensing authorities. The guidance will contain robust standards that I expect all licensing authorities to adopt, to ensure that all passengers, particularly children and vulnerable adults, are protected when using taxi and PHV services. We will also consult on revised best practice guidance which will include recommendations to licensing authorities to assist them in setting appropriate standards to enable the provision of services the public demand.</p><p> </p><p>At the recent Westminster Hall Debate on the ‘Regulation of working conditions in the private hire industry’ I announced my intention to set up a working group to consider how PHV and taxi licensing authorities use their powers. The group’s terms of reference and membership will be confirmed shortly.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-09-11T10:21:54.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756204/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756204/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Taxis: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that local authorities have a taxi licensing policy in place.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","7563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756205","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>Summary advice published on 5 September (available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/building-safety-programme-update-and-consolidated-advice-for-building-owners-following-large-scale-testing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/building-safety-programme-update-and-consolidated-advice-for-building-owners-following-large-scale-testing</a>) sets out the results of screening tests and the seven large-scale system tests conducted over the summer.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-12T13:33:09.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756205/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756205/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756205/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, pursuant to his Oral Statement of 3 July 2017, Official Report, column 912, on Grenfell Tower, how many of the 181 samples that failed fire tests had been used alongside (a) stone wool insulation and (b) PIR foam insulation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","7826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756206","Home Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>The temporary hold in place on applications with which the Supreme Court judgment was concerned was lifted on 10 August when changes to the Immigration Rules came into effect.</p><p> </p><p>As of 30 June 2017, there were around 5000 such applications on hold which are now being decided in accordance with the new Immigration Rules. We are unable to estimate how long it will take to consider the paused applications as it will depend on the individual circumstances of each case.</p><p> </p><p>More information regarding UK Visas and Immigration service standards can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/uk-visas-and-immigration/about-our-services" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/uk-visas-and-immigration/about-our-services</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-07T10:09:25.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756206/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756206/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-04","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Supreme Court judgment of 22 February 2017 and her Department's subsequent pause on decision-making on certain settlement applications, (a) how many of those applications are waiting to be processed, (b) what the average amount of time taken to process each application is and (c) what the timetable is for coming to a decision on all of those applications.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","7882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756207","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-11","<p>The department has contracts with 21 Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs), comprising both private and third sector organisations, who work alongside the National Probation Service (NPS) to supervise and reform offenders. These contracts contain a payment-by-results element linked to achieving reductions in reoffending.</p><p>The first set of final reoffending data for which CRCs could receive payment-by-results income will be published in October 2017; thereafter data will be published quarterly.</p><p>We continue to hold providers rigorously to account for their performance and are working to ensure they deliver services which reduce re-offending, protect the public and help offenders contribute to society.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-11T13:18:44.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756207/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756207/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Community Rehabilitation Companies: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of payment-by-results contracts on the delivery of services by community rehabilitation companies.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","7750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756208","Ministry of Justice","true","2017-09-11","<p>Electronic monitoring services in England and Wales have been provided by Capita plc since <del class="ministerial">2013</del><ins class="ministerial">2014</ins>. G4S, under a contract with the Department, provide the necessary hardware (electronic tags and home monitoring units) to support the service. The Department has robust processes in place to monitor and manage contractors and will not hesitate to take action when standards fall short.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-11T13:16:22.957Z","2017-11-17T16:43:22.173Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756208/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756208/answer","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756208/answer/previousversion/9419","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","G4S: Electronic Tagging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he has taken to improve the effectiveness of G4S in delivering electronic tagging services.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","7748"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756209","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-12","<p>Assisting offenders to secure suitable accommodation upon their release is a vital part of the Government’s approach to reducing reoffending.</p><p> </p><p>Through the commencement of the Homelessness Reduction Act (2017) and DCLG laying a statutory instrument. Prisons and Probation providers will be subject to the new duty to refer to the local housing authority someone who they support who might be at risk of becoming homeless.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to work with all providers to help make sure offenders get the support they need to find accommodation and employment on release.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-12T16:57:28.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756209/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756209/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Offenders: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what progress his Department has made on ensuring that all prisoners have a place to live on release from prison.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","7749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756210","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-11","<p>It is vital that offenders leaving prison are supported to lead successful and law-abiding lives in the community. That is why weIn 2014/15 the government reformed the probation system to strengthen its focus on reducing reoffending and protecting communities, and much progress has been made in implementing these reforms. For the first time around 40,000 offenders a year released from custodial sentences of less than 12 months are entitled to statutory support from probation on release, and new through-the-gate services have been introduced to improve the resettlement of released prisoners in the community. reformed the probation system to extend post-release supervision to all prisoners released from custody and introduce new through-the-gate resettlement services.</p><p>We understand that the current delivery of through-the-gate must improve and recognise the issues raised by Her Majesty’s Chief Inspectors of Prisons and Probation in their report published in June. We are working with providers to explore improvements that could be made to the delivery of rehabilitative services, and we continue to hold providers rigorously to account for their performance to ensure they deliver services which reduce re-offending, protect the public and help offenders contribute to society.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-11T16:33:28.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756210/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756210/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756210/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Reoffenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of the Through the Gate programme on reducing prisoner reoffending rates.","false","Biography information for Alex Sobel","Leeds North West","Alex Sobel","7751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756211","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>​A State Visit invitation has been offered and accepted. The precise dates and programme have yet to be confirmed. Once the dates are agreed, Government officials will begin work on the programme.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-09-12T15:14:22.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756211/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756211/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756211/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-04","USA: State Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will arrange for President Trump to meet representatives of the Muslim and ethnic minority communities during his forthcoming official visit to the UK.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","8144"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756212","Prime Minister","false","2017-09-12","<p>Dates of the telephone calls between myself and President Trump are available on the gov.uk website.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-09-12T14:21:47.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756212/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756212/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756212/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-09-04","Donald Trump","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, how many times since President Trump's inauguration she has made a telephone or other call to the President; and how many times she has received a telephone or other call from President Trump.","false","Biography information for Christian Matheson","City of Chester","Christian Matheson","8143"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756213","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-19","<p>The Government's Estate Regeneration National Strategy, published in December 2016, emphasises the key leadership role of local authorities in assessing and delivering the amount of social and affordable housing appropriate to meet the needs of their area. The National Strategy also sets out Government's expectations for how authorities should engage with residents throughout an estate regeneration scheme, and how residents should be protected. The Government's expectation is that all existing council and housing association tenants, whether on a lifetime or fixed tenancy, should have the option to return to the estate.</p><p>More than twice as much council housing has been built since 2010 than in the previous 13 years. 10,460 local authority dwellings were built between 2010-11 and 2016-17, up from 2,920 delivered over the previous 13 years (1997-98 to 2009-10). The Government recently announced plans to deliver more affordable homes, including at a social rent, by investing £2 billion in additional funding for housing associations and local councils in England. This will increase the Government’s 2016-21 Affordable Homes Programme in England to more than £9 billion.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-10-19T13:49:13.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756213/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756213/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756213/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Housing Estates: Regeneration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of the adequacy of the number of social and affordable housing units created by the redevelopment of local authority housing estates in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","7811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756214","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>A local authority may use receipts arising from the disposal of surplus housing land for any capital purpose, and they may assess the role of redevelopment projects on former local housing sites as part of their strategic or financial planning.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-12T12:55:03.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756214/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756214/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756214/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Housing Estates: Regeneration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of the role of redevelopment projects on former local authority housing sites in the financial planning of local authorities.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","7812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756215","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>My Department has no plans to restrict foreign ownership of new residential property in the UK, but will keep the issue under review. Research on foreign ownership of new build housing in London (LSE and York University for the Greater London Authority, May 2017) found that less than 20 per cent had been sold to foreign investors. Of this 20 per cent they have largely (70 per cent plus) been rented to Londoners. The report also outlined the importance of these sales in terms of pre-sales commitments to enable the construction of major developments.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-12T13:23:36.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756215/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756215/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756215/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Housing Estates: Regeneration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of the effect on the domestic housing market of the exclusive sale of housing units in regenerated urban estates to foreign and offshore investors.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","7810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756216","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-12","<p>Government policy is that a Compulsory Purchase Order will only be confirmed if there is a compelling case in the public interest.</p><p>When deciding whether or not confirm a compulsory purchase order, the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government is subject to the Public Sector Equality Duty in section 149 of the Equality Act 2010. He must have due regard to the need to (a) eliminate unlawful discrimination, harassment, victimisation; (b) advance equality of opportunity between persons who share a relevant protected characteristic and persons who do not share it; and (c) foster good relations between persons who share a relevant protected characteristic and persons who do not share it. The protected characteristics are: age, disability, gender reassignment, pregnancy and maternity, race, religion or belief, sex and sexual orientation</p><p>The Government has published a National Strategy for Estate Regeneration, which sets out government’s expectations for how landlords, developers and local authorities should engage with residents throughout an estate regeneration scheme, and for how residents should be protected.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-12T13:44:06.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756216/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756216/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756216/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-09-04","Compulsory Purchase","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of the effect on (a) individual homeowners and (b) social diversity in the affected area of compulsory purchase orders issued by local authorities in relation to regeneration projects.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","7809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756217","Home Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Government is committed to working with telecommunications operators to ensure that the security and intelligence agencies and law enforcement are able to access the data they need to protect the public.</p><p>In due course the Government will commence the provisions of the Investigatory Powers Act 2016 concerning technical capability notices and will bring forward regulations, on which we have already held a targeted consultation with relevant bodies. These regulations will set out the obligations which can be imposed on telecommunications and postal operators by such a notice.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben  Wallace",,"2017-09-07T16:38:47.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756217/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756217/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756217/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-04","Electronic Surveillance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to comments made by the former Director of GCHQ Robert Hannigan on the BBC's Today programme of 10 July 2017, if she will make an assessment of the potential merits of wider use of equipment interference warranty in conjunction with Section 253 notices requiring technology companies to maintain a capacity to provide access to individual devices as an alternative to any new Section 253 requirements on such companies to maintain a capacity to provide decrypts of messages sent using their communications software.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","7878"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756218","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-12","<p>On Friday 21st July, the Government published the summary of responses to our consultation on plans to ban the manufacture and sale of cosmetics and personal care products containing microbeads, which may cause harm to the marine environment. We will introduce legislation later this year. The consultation also asked for evidence on other sources of marine plastic pollution. We will use the responses to develop future UK action to protect the marine environment.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-12T13:46:58.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756218/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756218/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756218/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-04","Microplastics: Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if he will assess the environmental impact of the use of microplastics in industrial processes.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","8298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756219","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-12","<p>Microbeads from personal care products are believed to make up a small percentage of the total of microplastics entering the environment. European studies estimate that they may contribute from 0.1% to as much as 4.1% of microplastic pollution..</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-09-12T13:46:10.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756219/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756219/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756219/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-04","Microplastics: Cosmetics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what proportion of microbead-derived plastic which enters the natural environment originates in rinse-off cosmetics and personal care products.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","8299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756220","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>We are aware of reports that Mrs Mohammadi is suffering from a serious health condition requiring regular medical treatment not available in prison.</p><p>Mrs Mohammadi's case demonstrates Iran's appalling record when it comes to freedom of expression and we call on Iran to cease the harassment and detention of human rights defenders in the country.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-12T09:58:24.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756220/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756220/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756220/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-04","Narges Mohammadi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the effect on the health and welfare of Mrs Narges Mohammadi of her imprisonment in Iran.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","8308"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756221","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>​We are deeply concerned by the situation in Rakhine State and reports of a disproportionate response by the security forces to attacks by Rohingya militants. That is why on 30 August, the UK convened a discussion on Burma at the UN Security Council, where we urged restraint and called for all parties to de-escalate tensions. Along with the de-escalation of fighting, our immediate priority is how urgent food and medical assistance can be provided to displaced civilians from all communities. Also, our Embassy in Burma visited in Sittwe two weeks ago and plan to visit again imminently.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-12T16:06:43.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756221/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756221/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756221/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-04","Burma: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the accuracy of recent reports of a massacre in Chut Pyin village in the Sittwe District of Rakhine State, Myanmar.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","8310"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756222","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The British Government continues to discuss the situation in Rakhine with the Government of Burma. On 7 September, the Foreign Secretary called State Counsellor Aung San Suu Kyi to raise our strong concerns about Rakhine. They agreed any human rights abuses or violations must be investigated urgently. Our Ambassador continues to engage with officials from the Burmese Foreign Ministry on the full range of challenges facing Rakhine State.</p><p>On 30 August the UK convened a discussion on Burma at the UN Security Council. The UK urged the security forces in Rakhine to show restraint and called for all parties to de-escalate tensions. The Foreign Secretary released a statement on 2 September calling for an end to the violence. Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon made a statement at the 36th session of the Human Rights Council on 11 September which made clear that the UK strongly condemned the violence, and called on all parties to de-escalate tensions and address the humanitarian crisis.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2017-09-12T16:08:10.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756222/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756222/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756222/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-04","Burma: Rohingya","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what plans his Department has to respond to recent reports of the ethnic cleansing of Rohingya people in Rakhine State, Myanmar.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","8311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756224","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The case against Mohammad Ali Taheri demonstrates Iranian disregard for freedom of religion and belief. Religious minorities continue to face restrictions in Iran and we receive many reports of arrests, discrimination and harassment.</p><p>I raised concerns about the persecution of religious and ethnic minorities during my visit to Iran on 5 August. We will continue to take action with the international community to hold Iran to account in this regard.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-12T09:48:53.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756224/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756224/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756224/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-04","Mohammad Ali Taheri","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the case of the continuing imprisonment in Iran and repeated trial on charges which carry the death penalty of Mohammad Ali Taheri.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","8312"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756225","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-08","<p>We remain deeply concerned by the violence in the Central African Republic (CAR). Despite political progress in 2016, and good co-operation with the international community from the CAR government, the security situation outside of the capital city Bangui is deteriorating. This is having a heavy impact on the civilian population with thousands killed and tens of thousands displaced in 2017 alone. We are aware of United Nations (UN) Under-Secretary General Stephen O'Brien's report, which suggested that CAR is presenting &quot;early warning signs of genocide&quot;. It is true that the violence in CAR is often divided along religious lines, however, social, economic and political factors have been the primary drivers. We continue to call on the CAR government to implement the National Plan for Peacebuilding and Recovery, and will also be addressing, with our international partners, the human rights and humanitarian problems in CAR at the UN Human Rights Council later this month.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-09-08T11:42:13.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756225/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756225/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756225/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-04","Central African Republic: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of (a) inter-community violence, (b) political instability and (c) the risk of genocide in the Central African Republic.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","8313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756226","Home Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>The Poisons Act 1972 requires a supplier to report any relevant transaction(s) that they deem to be suspicious that involve substances listed in Part 3 of Schedule 1A.</p><p>Our policy is based on the following key strands:</p><p>Effective partnerships with relevant trade associations, suppliers and online retailers to help them understand which products are within scope of the Act, what action they should take to ensure compliance. Working with them and providing guidance to ensure they are able to spot and report suspicious transactions in a timely fashion.</p><p>Effective law enforcement by providing guidance to police officers on identifying non-compliance, preventing attacks, searching potential perpetrators for harmful substances and responding to victims at the scene.</p><p>Identifying where less harmful alternatives are available which achieve the same legitimate use.</p><p>Ensuring legislation covering the use of substances listed in Part 3 of Schedule 1A to the Poisons Act 1972 including acid and other corrosives is fit for purpose, that it is understood and consistently applied.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-07T16:05:59.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756226/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756226/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756226/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-04","Poisons: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how section 3(1)(c) of the Poisons Act 1972 is enforced for online retailers.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","8330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756227","Home Office","false","2017-09-07","<p>We are working closely with the National Police Chiefs' Council to identify what corrosive substances and chemicals are being used in attacks and to restrict access to these harmful products.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-07T15:59:14.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756227/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756227/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756227/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-04","Crimes of Violence: Corrosive Substances","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to identify the specific chemicals being used in corrosive substance attacks.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","8327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756228","Home Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>We recognise we require a range of partners to work together to tackle the use of acid and other corrosives in violent attacks, including police, health, local authorities, retailers and the voluntary sector. Our joint event on 4 July with the National Police Chiefs’ Council brought together a number of these partners to better understand the nature of attacks and agree what further action can be taken to prevent such attacks. The action plan has a range of actions including better data sharing between police and other partners such as health.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-09-12T15:22:25.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756228/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756228/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756228/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-04","Crimes of Violence: Acids","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to improve collaboration and information-sharing between public bodies including (a) NHS bodies, (b) police services and (c) local authorities in the response to attacks involving corrosive substances.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","8300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756229","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-07","<p>The detriment to retail energy customers on poor value standard variable tariffs, which was identified by the Competition and Markets Authority as averaging £1.4bn a year, must be addressed.</p><p> </p><p>My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State has written to the Chief Executive of Ofgem asking him to advise on what action the regulator intends to take to safeguard consumers on the poorest value tariffs and to consider the future of standard variable tariffs. The Secretary of State will consider further action in the light of Ofgem’s proposals and remains prepared to legislate if necessary.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-07T14:12:41.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756229/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756229/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756229/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans he has to introduce an energy price cap.","false","Biography information for Jenny Chapman","Darlington","Jenny Chapman","8225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756230","Department of Health","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that individuals make informed and safe choices about cosmetic interventions. Since publication of Sir Bruce Keogh’s Review of the Regulation of Cosmetic Interventions, in 2013, we have implemented a number of important changes to that end. A copy of the report is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/review-of-the-regulation-of-cosmetic-interventions" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/review-of-the-regulation-of-cosmetic-interventions</a></p><p> </p><p>We are considering options for the effective registration and regulation of those performing cosmetic interventions, and the Nuffield Council’s thorough and thoughtful report will help to inform our thinking about how to take this forward.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-09-12T13:58:44.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756230/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756230/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756230/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","Plastic Surgery: Ethics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if his Department will take steps to implement the recommendations of the Nuffield Council bioethics report, Cosmetic procedures: ethical issues, published in June 2017.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","8395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756231","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-12","<p>The Gulf Strategy Integrated Delivery Team has been allocated a budget of £850,000<br>in 2017-18.</p>","Ashford","Damian Green",,"2017-10-12T10:22:29.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756231/answer","Biography information for Damian Green","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756231/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756231/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-09-04","Gulf Strategy Unit: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what funding has been allocated to the Gulf Strategy Integrated Delivery Team for 2017-18.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756232","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>Pricing is a commercial decision for insurers which is affected by a wide range of factors and the taxes that insurers have to pay are just one part of this.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-12T10:20:40.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756232/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756232/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756232/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Insurance Premium Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 17 July 2017 to Question 4505, if he will make it his Department's policy to (a) monitor behavioural responses resulting from any change associated to prices of general insurance products following the recent increase in insurance premium tax and to (b) publish the findings of such monitoring.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756233","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-08","<p>The discussions on which the Treasury’s analysis of firms’ plans are based will continue until and beyond exit date. The Treasury has undertaken not to publish information shared by firms in confidence.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-08T12:59:30.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756233/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756233/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756233/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 14 July 2017 to Question 3386, when he expects to conclude his assessment; and if he plans to publish a report based on that assessment.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756234","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The government remains committed to the fiscal rules set out at the 2016 Autumn Statement which will guide us, via interim targets in 2020-21, back to balance by the middle of the next decade.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-09-12T10:39:51.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756234/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756234/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756234/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Public Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, in what year he plans to eliminate the deficit; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756235","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>At 31 March 2017 the amount of Tax Under Consideration for enquiries by HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) into the largest companies was £24.8 bn. Tax Under Consideration (TUC) is an HMRC measure on the maximum amount of tax that could potentially be collected from HMRC’s enquiries. TUC changes over time as enquiries progress and HMRC develop more certainty about the actual tax that needs to be paid. The TUC figure is different from the tax gap, which is the amount of tax HMRC legally expects to collect each year and the amount they actually collect. The UK’s overall tax gap has shown a long term fall, from 8.3% in 2005-06 to 6.5% in 2014-15 - one of lowest figures in the OECD.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-12T12:45:46.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756235/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756235/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756235/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Taxation: Multinational Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect on the public purse of the potential tax underpayment of £24.8 billion in 2016-17 by large companies identified by HM Revenue and Customs in August 2017; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756236","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-09-12","<p>The UK remains concerned about the cases of Ali Mohammed al-Nimr, Dawood al-Marhoon and Abdullah al-Zaher. Our Embassy in Riyadh last raised the three men's cases on 27 July. Our expectation remains that they will not be executed. We continue to closely follow their cases.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-09-12T08:36:12.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756236/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756236/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756236/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-09-04","Saudi Arabia: Capital Punishment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent representations he has made to his Saudi Arabian counterpart on the cases of Ali Mohammed al-Nimr, Dawood al-Marhoon and Abdullah al-Zaher.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756237","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-11","<p>Initial Operating Capability for Watchkeeper was met in August 2014 and it deployed on Operations in Afghanistan. Full operating capability is forecast to be achieved in 2018. The current total financial approval for development and delivery of Watchkeeper is £927 million.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","8078","2017-09-11T15:41:33.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756237/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756237/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756237/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-04","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the current total financial approval is for the development and delivery of the Watchkeeper to full operating capacity.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8089"
