"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756254","Department for Transport","false","2017-09-11","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency is in negotiations with the landlord of Baillieston test centre in respect of a further lease of the property and continued occupation of the premises.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-09-11T10:49:17.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756254/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756254/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756254/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-09-04","Driving Tests: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 27 June 2017 to Question 99, what options are being considered by his Department for Baillieston DVSA test centre in Glasgow when the current property rental contract expires.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756255","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>Our work coaches personalise the support provided for each claimant based on individual need and circumstance. Where claimants have limitations due to a health condition or disability or because of caring responsibilities, then this is taken into account when arranging any attendance.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to offer internet access to support claimants and we are working with local authorities as part of our ongoing partnership to improve digital access and capability.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T14:33:01.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756255/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756255/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756255/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the closure of Easterhouse Jobcentre on claimants who have difficulty using PCs and the internet.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756256","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>Our work coaches personalise the support provided for each claimant based on individual need and circumstance. Where claimants have limitations due to a health condition or disability or because of caring responsibilities, then this is taken into account when arranging any attendance.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to offer internet access to support claimants and we are working with local authorities as part of our ongoing partnership to improve digital access and capability.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T14:12:31.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756256/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756256/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756256/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the closure of Parkhead Jobcentre on claimants who have difficulty using PCs and the internet.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756257","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>In the 12 month period from 1 September 2016 to 31 August 2017, the average time taken to allocate a complaint to an investigation case manager was 45 weeks.</p><p> </p><p>Improvements in complaint handling within DWP mean that the ICE Office receive far fewer cases which can be resolved, to the complainant’s satisfaction, without a full investigation of the evidence. This means that the ICE process is reserved for more complex cases which are, by nature, more time consuming.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-12T16:34:56.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756257/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756257/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756257/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Social Security Benefits: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average waiting time for a complaint lodged with the Independent Case Examiner to be allocated to an investigation case manager was in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756258","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>The information is not available.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-11T16:51:53.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756258/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756258/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756258/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Social Security Benefits: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make it his Department's policy to collect information of individuals subject to a benefit sanction who receive assistance from a food bank during the period of sanction; and if he will publish that information.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756259","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-08","<p>The detriment to retail energy customers on poor value standard variable tariffs, which was identified by the Competition and Market Authority as averaging £1.4bn a year, must be addressed.</p><p>My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State has written to the Chief Executive of Ofgem asking him to advise on what action the regulator intends to take to safeguard consumers on the poorest value tariffs and to consider the future of standard variable tariffs. The Secretary of State will consider further action in the light of Ofgem’s proposals and remains prepared to legislate if necessary.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-08T14:23:26.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756259/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756259/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756259/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Energy: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the Government plans to introduce a safeguard tariff cap.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756260","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-07","<p>Support for businesses in Scotland is largely a devolved matter, and <a href="https://www.mygov.scot/business" target="_blank">https://www.mygov.scot/business</a> provides advice to people starting, running and growing a business, including a section on funding and grants in Scotland. In addition, British Business Bank (BBB) programmes are supporting finance to smaller businesses. Since November 2014, BBB programmes have facilitated around £2.2m* to 71 businesses in the constituency of Glasgow East. This includes 49 start-up loans totalling over £250,000.</p><p>Alongside designing and delivering programmes through its partners, the British Business Bank works to promote the provision of better information in the market to increase smaller businesses’ understanding of the finance options available to them. The Business Finance Guide (<a href="http://www.thebusinessfinanceguide.co.uk/bbb" target="_blank">http://www.thebusinessfinanceguide.co.uk/bbb</a> ) sets out the different sources of finance available to businesses – from start-ups to SMEs and growing mid-sized companies.</p><p>In order to support innovation by small businesses, Innovate UK awarded 99 projects to SMEs in Scotland with a commitment of £16.7 million in 2016/17.</p><p>Small businesses in Scotland also benefit from UK-wide initiatives to encourage investment, for example the Enterprise Investment Scheme and the Seed Enterprise Investment Scheme. If they have business premises, small businesses will also benefit from the Small Business Bonus Scheme and receive 100% relief on their rates bill for property valued below £10,000.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em>*This does not include ENABLE funding data as this is not available at a constituency level.</em></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-07T15:40:35.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756260/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756260/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756260/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Small Businesses: Glasgow East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to support micro-enterprises in Glasgow East constituency.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756261","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>As at the end of February 2017, there were 14,270 State Pension recipients in Glasgow East, with an average age of 74.1 years, and 19,920 recipients in Maidenhead, with an average age of 75.0 years.</p><p> </p><p><em>Source: DWP Work and Pensions Longitudinal Study, February 2017.</em></p><p><em>Caseload figures have been rounded to the nearest 10.</em></p><p><em>Averages are means.</em></p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-09-12T10:01:30.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756261/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756261/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756261/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Pensioners: Glasgow East and Maidenhead","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the (a) number and (b) average age was of state pension recipients in (i) Glasgow East and (ii) Maidenhead constituencies in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756262","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>Child Support Agency <br></p><p>a) As at July 2017 the total value of arrears on Child Support Agency cases in the Glasgow East constituency stood at £5.50m.</p><p> </p><p>b) As at July 2017 the total value of arrears on Child Support Agency cases in Scotland stood at £243.22m.</p><p> </p><p>Child Maintenance Service</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Information on the total value of arrears on cases in the Glasgow East, and in Scotland, for the Child Maintenance Service could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>1) Numbers are rounded to the nearest 10,000.</p><p> </p><p>2) Cases have been allocated to Glasgow East parliamentary constituency by matching the residential postcode of the parent with care for all cases administered on the CS2 and CSCS computer systems, as well as cases managed off system, to the Office for National Statistics Postcode Directory.</p><p> </p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-11T14:07:16.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756262/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756262/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756262/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the total amount of child maintenance arrears was in (a) Glasgow East constituency and (b) Scotland in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7652"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756263","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>a) As at July 2017 there were 1,640 parents with care with a Child Support Agency case in the Glasgow East constituency.</p><p> </p><p>b) As at July 2017 there were 1,560 non-resident parents with a Child Support Agency case in the Glasgow East constituency.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p> </p><ol><li>Figures rounded to the nearest 10.</li></ol><p> </p><ol start="2"><li>Cases have been allocated to Glasgow East parliamentary constituency by matching the residential postcode of the parent with care and non-resident parent for all cases administered on the CS2 and CSCS computer systems, as well as cases managed off system, to the Office for National Statistics Postcode Directory.</li></ol><p> </p><ol start="3"><li>The number of parents with care and non-resident parents is a unique count of individuals within this constituency it is possible for either parent to have more than one Child Support Agency case.</li></ol><p> </p><ol start="4"><li>It cannot be assumed that parents with care in a) above, and non-resident parents in b) above, are connected to the same case although some may be. A number of the non-resident parents who reside in Glasgow East constituency will be connected to a Child Support Agency case with a parent with care who resides elsewhere in the country. Equally, a number of the parents with care who reside in Glasgow East constituency will be connected to with a non-resident parent who resides elsewhere in the country.</li></ol><p> </p><ol start="5"><li>A national insurance number was not present in the system at time of this data extract for a very small number of parents with care and non-resident parents, it has therefore not been possible to allocate these to a specific parliamentary constituency.</li></ol>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-11T11:52:28.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756263/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756263/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756263/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Lone Parents: Glasgow East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many (a) parents with care and (b) non-resident parents there were in Glasgow East constituency with a Child Support Agency case in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756264","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>a) As at July 2017, there were 1,520 arrears only cases in the Glasgow East constituency held by the Child Support Agency.</p><p> </p><p>b) As at July 2017, there were 160 arrears cases involving a current liability in the Glasgow East constituency held by the Child Support Agency.</p><p> </p><p>Notes:<br></p><p>1) Numbers are rounded to the nearest 10.</p><p> </p><p>2) Cases have been allocated to a Glasgow East parliamentary constituency by matching the residential postcode of the parent with care for all cases administered on the CS2 and CSCS computer systems, as well as cases managed off system, to the Office for National Statistics Postcode Directory.</p><p> </p><p>3) A case is classed as having a ‘Current Liability’ if it is open, has children of a qualifying age and has a positive liability (i.e. assessment to pay maintenance). This includes cases due to pay via Maintenance Direct.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-11T11:59:31.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756264/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756264/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756264/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many Child Support Agency (a) arrears-only and (b) arrears cases involving a current liability for a child there are in Glasgow East constituency.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756265","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>Table 1, below, shows the number of individuals in Glasgow East constituency who underwent DLA to PIP reassessment and had their award (a) increased, (b) kept the same and (c) decreased in each calendar year for which figures are available.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Table 1 – increased, equal and decreased awards following reassessment for PIP in Glasgow East</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Table 1</p></td><td><p>(a) Increased</p></td><td><p>(b) Equal</p></td><td><p>(c) Decreased</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jan to Dec 2014</p></td><td><p>#</p></td><td><p>#</p></td><td><p>#</p></td><td><p>#</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jan to Dec 2015</p></td><td><p>230</p></td><td><p>40</p></td><td><p>200</p></td><td><p>460</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jan to Oct 2016</p></td><td><p>400</p></td><td><p>140</p></td><td><p>450</p></td><td><p>980</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>630</p></td><td><p>170</p></td><td><p>650</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Table 2, below, shows the average (mean) amount by which awards to individuals in Glasgow East constituency who underwent DLA to PIP reassessment (i) increased and (ii) decreased in each calendar year for which figures are available.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Table 2 – average (mean £) increase and decrease in awards following reassessment for PIP in Glasgow East</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Table 2</p></td><td><p>(i) Average (mean) increase</p></td><td><p>(ii) Average (mean) decrease</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jan to Dec 2014</p></td><td><p>#</p></td><td><p>#</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jan to Dec 2015</p></td><td><p>£45.77</p></td><td><p>-£47.48</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jan to Oct 2016</p></td><td><p>£46.28</p></td><td><p>-£46.01</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>For both tables, October 2016 is the latest published data available. Later data is available on DWP systems but has been withheld as it will be published as part of official statistics in December 2017.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Figures have been rounded to the nearest 10. ‘#’ indicates a total of less than 5. Columns may not sum due to rounding.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-12T12:31:46.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756265/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756265/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756265/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Personal Independence Payment: Glasgow East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many disability living allowance claimants who have been invited to and claimed personal independence payment in Glasgow East constituency have had their award (a) increased, (b) kept the same and (c) decreased; and what the average amount was by which awards (i) increased and (ii) decreased in each year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756266","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>At this point in time there are no DWP employees who are currently based at Parkhead Jobcentre who are at risk of redundancy as a result of the planned closure.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-11T14:22:23.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756266/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756266/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756266/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether any compulsory redundancies are planned as a result of the closure of Parkhead Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756267","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The information requested is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-12T14:02:19.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756267/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756267/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756267/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Personal Independence Payment: Glasgow East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many disability living allowance claimants in Glasgow East constituency have been invited to but have not claimed personal independence payment in each year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756268","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>Jobcentre distances and journey times were calculated using a variety of methods to ensure as accurate an assessment as possible, recognising the number of variables that might factor in claimants actual journeys. This included online tools and timetables, information collected on local public transport routes, and input and scrutiny from local DWP colleagues and management.</p><p> </p><p>We will publicise dates and inform customers when their jobcentres close in advance. We recognise that some claimants will be taking an unfamiliar journey: work coaches will support these people over the transition period until they become familiar with their new travel arrangements. Claimants can also make a request to attend a jobcentre that is closer to their home, or with more convenient travel links, if that better suits their needs. Our work coaches will help signpost claimants in such circumstances.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T14:48:38.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756268/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756268/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756268/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Job Centres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of using Ordnance Survey automated software to (a) calculate routes, estimated journey times and distances for each current customer of Parkhead Jobcentre to travel from their place of residence to Shettleston Jobcentre by public transport, (b) supply each customer with their information prior to the closure of Parkhead Jobcentre and (c) publish this data in an anonymised format.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756269","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The table below shows the number of Personal Independence Payment (PIP) Mandatory Reconsideration decisions and appeal decisions where the award was changed by year of each decision since the introduction of PIP in the Parliamentary Constituencies of Glasgow East.</p><p> </p><p><em>Number of Mandatory Reconsiderations decisions and appeal decisions where the award changed, by financial year of decision.</em></p><p><em> </em></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year of Mandatory Reconsideration</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/ 15</p></td><td><p>2015/ 16</p></td><td><p>2016/ 17</p></td><td><p>2017/18 (April 17 only)</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of Awards Changed at Mandatory Reconsideration</p></td><td><p>#</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>60</p></td><td><p>140</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>230</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year of Appeal Decision</p></td><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2014/ 15</p></td><td><p>2015/ 16</p></td><td><p>2016/ 17</p></td><td><p>2017/18 (April 17 only)</p></td><td><p>Total</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Number of Awards Changed at Appeal</p></td><td><p>#</p></td><td><p>20</p></td><td><p>140</p></td><td><p>150</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>320</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-12T12:18:26.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756269/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756269/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756269/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Personal Independence Payment: Glasgow East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in Glasgow East constituency have had their original decision on claiming personal independence payments overturned as a result of (a) mandatory reconsideration and (b) an appeal hearing in each year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756270","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>Jobcentre distances and journey times were calculated using a variety of methods to ensure as accurate an assessment as possible, recognising the number of variables that might factor in claimants actual journeys. This included online tools and timetables, information collected on local public transport routes, and input and scrutiny from local DWP colleagues and management.</p><p> </p><p>We will publicise dates and inform customers when their jobcentres close in advance. We recognise that some claimants will be taking an unfamiliar journey: work coaches will support these people over the transition period until they become familiar with their new travel arrangements. Claimants can also make a request to attend a jobcentre that is closer to their home, or with more convenient travel links, if that better suits their needs. Our work coaches will help signpost claimants in such circumstances.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T14:42:32.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756270/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756270/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756270/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Job Centres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of using ordnance survey automated software to (a) calculate routes, estimated journey times and distances for each current customer of Easterhouse Jobcentre to travel from their place of residence to Shettleston Jobcentre by public transport, (b) supply each customer with their information prior to the closure of Easterhouse Jobcentre and (c) publish that data in an anonymised format.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756271","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>As at February 2014, the amount deducted from housing benefit claimants in Glasgow East parliamentary constituency due to the removal of the spare room subsidy was 24.4 thousand pounds per week, rising to 30.4 thousand pounds per week, an increase of 6.1 thousand pounds per week.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-11T12:11:50.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756271/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756271/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756271/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Housing Benefit: Glasgow East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an estimate of the change in the amount deducted from housing benefit claimants in Glasgow East constituency due to the removal of the spare room subsidy between February 2014 and May 2017.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756272","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The increased use of our online services in recent years, coupled with reductions in unemployment and improved efficiency means that 20% of the rent currently paid by DWP is going toward space we are not using. In response, we have sought to redesign our estate in a way that delivers value for the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>The city of Glasgow has a higher number of jobcentres than comparable cities across the UK and our revised estate balances the need for an accessible network with best use of taxpayers money. The decision to close Parkhead was not taken in isolation but was as part of our service design for the Glasgow area as a whole.</p><p> </p><p>We would stress that this is not about reducing services, it is about taking the opportunity to stop spending money on empty space so we can spend more on supporting those in need.</p><p> </p><p>This has given us a unique opportunity to review which offices we will need in the future, taking account of the impact of Universal Credit and the anticipated demand on our services.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T14:26:46.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756272/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756272/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756272/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what specific options were considered for the future of Parkhead Jobcentre prior to the decision to divest.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756273","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The increased use of our online services in recent years, coupled with reductions in unemployment and improved efficiency means that 20% of the rent currently paid by DWP is going toward space we are not using. In response, we have sought to redesign our estate in a way that delivers value for the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>The city of Glasgow has a higher number of jobcentres than comparable cities across the UK and our revised estate balances the need for an accessible network with best use of taxpayers money. The decision to close Easterhouse was not taken in isolation but was as part of our service design for the Glasgow area as a whole.</p><p> </p><p>We would stress that this is not about reducing services, it is about taking the opportunity to stop spending money on empty space so we can spend more on supporting those in need.</p><p> </p><p>This has given us a unique opportunity to review which offices we will need in the future, taking account of the impact of Universal Credit and the anticipated demand on our services.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T14:31:18.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756273/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756273/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756273/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what specific options were considered for the future of Easterhouse Jobcentre prior to the decision to divest.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756274","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>Jobcentre Plus does not make direct referrals to food banks but has offered a signposting service since 2011 to those who have expressed an interest in using a food bank. No data is held on the number using the signposting service at Easterhouse, Parkhead and Shettleston Jobcentres.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","8087 ; 8088","2017-09-11T17:05:19.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756274/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756274/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756274/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of people who have been either signposted or referred to a food bank by staff at Easterhouse jobcentre in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756275","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>Customers are usually assigned to their nearest Jobcentre according to their postcode when making a claim. However, claimants can elect to change the Jobcentre they attend.</p><p>Where we are proposing changes to our estate we have provided details of the future locations of our sites so that our claimants can understand the impact on their travel arrangements</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T10:53:59.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756275/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756275/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756275/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobseeker's Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what criteria are used to determine to which Jobcentre Plus office each new claim is assigned.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756276","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>Jobcentre Plus does not make direct referrals to food banks but has offered a signposting service since 2011 to those who have expressed an interest in using a food bank. No data is held on the number using the signposting service at Easterhouse, Parkhead and Shettleston Jobcentres.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","8086 ; 8088","2017-09-11T17:05:19.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756276/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756276/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756276/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of people who have been either signposted or referred to a food bank by staff at Parkhead jobcentre in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756277","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>The following Ministers have visited a food bank since their appointment. The Rt. Hon. David Gauke MP, Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, visited a food bank on 7 July 2017. Damian Hinds MP, Minister of State for Employment, visited a food bank on 21 July 2017. Guy Opperman MP, Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Pensions and Financial Inclusion visited a food bank on 31 August 2017.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-11T15:29:42.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756277/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756277/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756277/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Food Banks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, which Ministers of his Department have visited a food bank since their appointment; and what the date of each such visit was.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756278","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The department is working in partnership with organisations to offer support to claimants and will continue to do so. DWP recognises the need to ensure support for claimants is coordinated and that there are many partner organisations within the Parkhead area who offer valuable services for claimants.</p><p> </p><p>Our Partnership Managers are in regular contact with third sector organisations and information on services is made available to Work Coaches to enable signposting of claimants. For example, through the Universal Credit Delivery Partnership Agreement, DWP funds Glasgow City Council to provide initial and ongoing online support to claimants in three library hub locations (Gorbals, Anniesland and Shettleston).</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T10:51:26.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756278/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756278/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756278/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent discussions he has had with third sector organisations on the closure of Parkhead Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756279","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>Jobcentre Plus does not make direct referrals to food banks but has offered a signposting service since 2011 to those who have expressed an interest in using a food bank. No data is held on the number using the signposting service at Easterhouse, Parkhead and Shettleston Jobcentres.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","8086 ; 8087","2017-09-11T17:05:19.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756279/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756279/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756279/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of people who have been either signposted or referred to a food bank by staff at Shettleston jobcentre in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756280","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>We are not yet in a position to share an estimated figure due to commercial confidentiality pending completion of legal processes. We expect to make savings by merging offices through reduced running costs and making best use of both office space available and taxpayer’s money.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T14:23:39.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756280/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756280/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756280/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the savings to the public purse which will accrue from the proposed closure of Parkhead Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756281","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>We are not yet in a position to share an estimated figure due to commercial confidentiality pending completion of legal processes. We expect to make savings by merging offices through reduced running costs and making best use of both office space available and taxpayer’s money.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T14:51:06.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756281/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756281/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756281/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the savings to the public purse which will accrue from the proposed closure of Easterhouse Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756282","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>As at 31 August 2017 there were 1,854 cases awaiting allocation to an investigation case manager.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-12T16:31:54.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756282/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756282/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756282/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Social Security Benefits: Complaints","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many complaints have been accepted for investigation by the Independent Case Examiner's Office but have yet to be allocated to an investigation case manager in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8085"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756283","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>Ministers visit Jobcentres and other DWP locations across the UK regularly through the year. It is not however generally possible to specify in advance which locations this will include.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T10:05:53.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756283/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756283/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756283/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 29 June 2017 to Question 111, if (a) he and (b) a Minister of his Department will visit Easterhouse Jobcentre Plus in 2017.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756284","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>The current FRS sample of 20,000 households a year already makes it one of the largest social surveys in the UK. It is designed to be representative at a country / region level (13 areas), and even at this geography results are often presented as a three-year average. Expanding this to be representative at local authority level would require a huge increase in the sample, which even if practicable, would involve significant additional spending in the order of millions of pounds.</p><p> </p><p>The government is trying to help local authorities understand and monitor disadvantage within their area. Improving Lives: Helping Workless Families, published on 4 April, sets out statutory and non-statutory indicators to provide a framework for a continued focus on improving outcomes for disadvantaged families and children, now and over time. As part of this, we have made available the latest analysis and an evidence base to enable local authorities, local partners and others to understand, and act on, the complex factors of disadvantage in their local area. This includes local-level data on the factors of disadvantage that is available through a local government data tool (LG Inform).</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-11T14:16:09.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756284/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756284/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756284/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 27 June 2017 to Question 97, if he will make it his Department's policy to work with relevant bodies to increase the survey sample sizes to support the production of robust estimates of the number of children in relative low income at constituency and local authority level.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756285","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The information is not readily available and has not previously been published as official statistics. We will consider whether it is feasible to produce the statistics requested within the disproportionate cost limit, and if so, will issue them in an official statistics release in accordance with the Code of Practice for Official Statistics.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-09-12T12:40:40.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756285/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756285/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756285/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Access to Work Programme: Glasgow East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in Glasgow East constituency received support through the Access to Work scheme in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756286","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>Ministers visit Jobcentres and other DWP locations across the UK regularly through the year. It is not however generally possible to specify in advance which locations this will include.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T13:14:24.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756286/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756286/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756286/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 29 June 2017 to Question 115, if (a) he and (b) a Minister of his Department will visit Shettleston Jobcentre Plus in 2017.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756287","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>Ministers visit Jobcentres and other DWP locations across the UK regularly through the year. It is not however generally possible to specify in advance which locations this will include.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T13:16:10.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756287/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756287/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756287/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 29 June 2017 to Question 112, if (a) he and (b) a Minister of his Department will visit Parkhead Jobcentre Plus in 2017.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756288","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>The increased use of our online services in recent years, coupled with reductions in unemployment and improved efficiency means that 20% of the rent currently paid by DWP is going toward space we are not using. In response, we have sought to redesign our estate in a way that delivers value for the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>The city of Glasgow has a higher number of jobcentres than comparable cities across the UK and our revised estate balances the need for an accessible network with best use of taxpayers money. The decision to close Easterhouse was not taken in isolation but was as part of our service design for the Glasgow area as a whole.</p><p> </p><p>We would stress that this is not about reducing services, it is about taking the opportunity to stop spending money on empty space so we can spend more on supporting those in need.</p><p> </p><p>This has given us a unique opportunity to review which offices we will need in the future, taking account of the impact of Universal Credit and the anticipated demand on our services.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-11T16:50:01.483Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756288/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756288/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756288/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, by what criteria Easterhouse Jobcentre has been selected for closure.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756289","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>At this point in time there are no DWP employees who are currently based at Parkhead Jobcentre who are at risk of redundancy as a result of the planned closure.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-11T15:31:23.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756289/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756289/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756289/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether there are plans for compulsory redundancies as a result of the closure of the Parkhead jobcentre.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756290","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>The increased use of our online services in recent years, coupled with reductions in unemployment and improved efficiency means that 20% of the rent currently paid by DWP is going toward space we are not using. In response, we have sought to redesign our estate in a way that delivers value for the taxpayer.</p><p> </p><p>The city of Glasgow has a higher number of jobcentres than comparable cities across the UK and our revised estate balances the need for an accessible network with best use of taxpayers money. The decision to close Parkhead was not taken in isolation but was as part of our service design for the Glasgow area as a whole.</p><p> </p><p>We would stress that this is not about reducing services, it is about taking the opportunity to stop spending money on empty space so we can spend more on supporting those in need.</p><p> </p><p>This has given us a unique opportunity to review which offices we will need in the future, taking account of the impact of Universal Credit and the anticipated demand on our services.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-11T16:35:02.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756290/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756290/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756290/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, by what criteria Parkhead Jobcentre has been selected for closure.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756291","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The department will support customers through the change of their Jobcentre’s location and as part of that support we will advise them on alternative Jobcentre locations, taking into account travel.</p><p> </p><p>Local consultation for offices over three miles and 20 minutes away by public transport, will help inform decisions about additional provision. Parkhead Jobcentre to Shettleston Jobcentre is 1.1 miles away. Journey times are from 11 minutes upwards, depending upon the mode of public transport used.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T16:22:31.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756291/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756291/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756291/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the (a) distance and (b) time it will take to travel by public transport from Parkhead Jobcentre to Shettleston Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756292","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The department will support customers through the change of their Jobcentre’s location and as part of that support we will advise them on alternative Jobcentre locations, taking into account travel.</p><p> </p><p>Local consultation for offices over three miles and 20 minutes away by public transport, will help inform decisions about additional provision. Easterhouse Jobcentre to Shettleston Jobcentre is 2.9 miles away. Journey times are from 19 minutes upwards, depending upon the mode of public transport used.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T16:19:55.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756292/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756292/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756292/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the (a) distance and (b) time it will take to travel by public transport from Easterhouse Jobcentre to Shettleston Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8061"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756293","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>Our work coaches personalise the support provided for each claimant based on individual need and circumstance. We will continue to offer internet access from Shettleston Jobcentre to support claimants and we are working with local authorities as part of our on-going partnership to improve digital access and capability.</p><p> </p><p>If claimants are experiencing any difficulties with the service, they should discuss their issues with their Work Coach who will be happy to help overcome any issues affecting their claim or work search.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T10:47:18.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756293/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756293/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756293/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobseeker's Allowance: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps the Government has taken to extend the availability of public access terminals in areas served by Parkhead Jobcentre after it closes.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8062"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756294","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>Our work coaches personalise the support provided for each claimant based on individual need and circumstance. We will continue to offer internet access from Shettleston Jobcentre to support claimants and we are working with local authorities as part of our on-going partnership to improve digital access and capability.</p><p> </p><p>If claimants are experiencing any difficulties with the service, they should discuss their issues with their Work Coach who will be happy to help overcome any issues affecting their claim or work search.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T10:49:21.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756294/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756294/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756294/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobseeker's Allowance: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps the Government has taken to extend the availability of public access terminals in areas served by Easterhouse Jobcentre after it closes.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756295","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>The information relating specifically to how many times the public WiFi at Parkhead Jobcentre has been accessed by different devices is not held by DWP or the supplier. However, the latest data for July 2017 shows 975 unique Wi-Fi connections in Parkhead Jobcentre. The Wi-Fi connection at Parkhead Jobcentre is public and as a result the members of the public are able to access the Wi-Fi from inside the office or immediately outside so the number of connections would not relate to only Jobcentre customers using the service.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-11T14:12:46.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756295/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756295/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756295/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many times the public WiFi at Parkhead Jobcentre has been accessed by a different device in the latest period for which data is available.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756296","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The information relating specifically to how many times the public WiFi at Easterhouse Jobcentre has been accessed by different devices is not held by DWP or the supplier. However, the latest data for July 2017 shows 600 unique Wi-Fi connections in Easterhouse Jobcentre. The Wi-Fi connection at Easterhouse Jobcentre is public and as a result the members of the public are able to access the Wi-Fi from inside the office or immediately outside so the number of connections would not relate to only Jobcentre customers using the service.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-12T16:02:42.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756296/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756296/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756296/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many times the public WiFi at Easterhouse Jobcentre has been accessed by a different device in the latest period for which data is available.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756297","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The most detailed and up-to-date UK labour market statistics are available from official sources from: <a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/</a>. These figures are rounded to the nearest five.</p><p> </p><p>Our Work Coaches personalise the support they provide for each claimant based on individual need and circumstance, including the offer of home visits and postal signing where appropriate. The needs of vulnerable claimants, such as those limited by a health condition or disability or because of caring responsibilities, are taken into account when arranging any attendance.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T12:51:08.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756297/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756297/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756297/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants are served by Shettleston Jobcentre; and how many of those claimants are disabled.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756298","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>Easterhouse Jobcentre is a leased building which the landlord can offer to new tenants once DWP has vacated the building.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T13:07:15.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756298/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756298/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756298/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect on the local economy of the plan to relocate jobs from Easterhouse Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8047"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756299","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>Parkhead Jobcentre is a leased building which the landlord can offer to new tenants once DWP has vacated the building.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T13:12:14.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756299/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756299/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756299/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect on the local economy of the plan to relocate jobs from Parkhead Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756300","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The information requested is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Statistics are available on the number of self-identified disabled people who have received an adverse sanction decision whilst in receipt of Employment and Support Allowance (ESA), Income Support or Jobseeker’s Allowance and these are published on Stat-Xplore here: <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to extract the relevant information can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started.html</a></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T10:13:08.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756300/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756300/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756300/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Disability: Glasgow East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an estimate of the proportion of disabled people in Glasgow East constituency who were subject to an adverse sanction decision in 2016.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8049"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756301","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>There is a phased closure programme in place for all offices affected by the People and Locations Programme.</p><p> </p><p>The closure date for Parkhead Jobcentre is 16 February 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Posters will be on display in Parkhead Jobcentre at least 2 months before the closure date.</p><p> </p><p>All customers who attend the Jobcentre will receive a letter about the change within one month of the closure date. Work Coaches and Service delivery colleagues will also verbally advise customers about the closure as part of routine interviews and at all other attendance.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, DWP have already notified partners and stakeholders in writing to confirm changes to estate across the city, including Parkhead. To enhance wider communications, posters will be on display in as many venues and partner organisations in local communities as possible and DWP will work with local press, radio and other media sources aiming to cascade information about office changes as widely as possible. All activities referred to will be in addition to the work we will carry out internally to notify customers about changes in advance of closure dates.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T10:09:47.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756301/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756301/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756301/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people who use Parkhead Jobcentre have been informed in writing of the closure of that jobcentre.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756302","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>We are not yet in a position to share an estimated figure due to commercial confidentiality pending completion of legal processes. We expect to make savings by merging offices through reduced running costs and making best use of both office space available and taxpayer’s money.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T10:07:26.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756302/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756302/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756302/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the cost of the relocation of staff and resources from Parkhead Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8051"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756303","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The most detailed and up-to-date UK labour market statistics are available from official sources from: <a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/</a>. These figures are rounded to the nearest five.</p><p> </p><p>Our Work Coaches personalise the support they provide for each claimant based on individual need and circumstance, including the offer of home visits and postal signing where appropriate. The needs of vulnerable claimants, such as those limited by a health condition or disability or because of caring responsibilities, are taken into account when arranging any attendance.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T12:55:17.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756303/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756303/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756303/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants are served by Parkhead Jobcentre; and how many of those claimants are disabled.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756304","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>The most detailed and up-to-date UK labour market statistics are available from official sources from: <a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/</a>. These figures are rounded to the nearest five.</p><p> </p><p>Our Work Coaches personalise the support they provide for each claimant based on individual need and circumstance, including the offer of home visits and postal signing where appropriate. The needs of vulnerable claimants, such as those limited by a health condition or disability or because of caring responsibilities, are taken into account when arranging any attendance.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T13:57:06.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756304/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756304/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756304/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants are served by Easterhouse Jobcentre; and how many of those claimants are disabled.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756305","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>Equality analyses are not routinely separately published. However, throughout the redesign of our estate the department has been mindful of its duties under section 149 of the Equality Act 2010 and the impact of its plans on its colleagues and customers</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T13:03:21.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756305/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756305/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756305/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he plans to publish an equality impact assessment on the closure of Easterhouse Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8054"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756306","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>Equality analyses are not routinely separately published. However, throughout the redesign of our estate the department has been mindful of its duties under section 149 of the Equality Act 2010 and the impact of its plans on its colleagues and customers.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T13:10:21.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756306/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756306/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756306/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he plans to publish an equality impact assessment on the closure of Parkhead Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8055"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756307","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>We are not yet in a position to share an estimated figure due to commercial confidentiality pending completion of legal processes. We expect to make savings by merging offices through reduced running costs and making best use of both office space available and taxpayer’s money.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T14:47:06.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756307/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756307/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756307/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate his Department has made of the cost of relocating staff and resources from Easterhouse Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756308","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>There is a phased closure programme in place for all offices affected by the People and Locations Programme.</p><p> </p><p>The closure date for Easterhouse Jobcentre is 9 February 2018.</p><p> </p><p>All customers who attend the Jobcentre will receive a letter about the change within one month of the closure date. Work Coaches and Service delivery colleagues will also verbally advise customers about the closure as part of routine interviews and at all other attendance.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, DWP have already notified partners and stakeholders in writing to confirm changes to estate across the city, including Easterhouse. To enhance wider communications, posters will be on display in as many venues and partner organisations in local communities as possible and DWP will work with local press, radio and other media sources aiming to cascade information about office changes as widely as possible. All activities referred to will be in addition to the work we will carry out internally to notify customers about changes in advance of closure dates.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T12:38:17.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756308/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756308/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756308/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people who use Easterhouse Jobcentre have been informed in writing of the closure of that jobcentre.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756309","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>We are committed to retaining an accessible jobcentre network and continuing to serve customers in all areas of the country, including Glasgow.</p><p> </p><p>As part of that commitment we are working with partner organisations throughout Glasgow, collaborating with them to ensure individuals have access to the widest range of support during periods of unemployment. This is in addition to the core services available via the local jobcentre.</p><p> </p><p>We are already working closely with Glasgow City Council and a significant amount of work to increase support for homeless customers has been on going over the past year with City Mission and Simon Community. We are also working with Glasgow Community Planning and Skills Development Scotland to explore outreach opportunities and closer working.</p><p> </p><p>There are also plans in place to host local stakeholder/partnership meetings where third sector and other employability and support organisations will be invited to attend. This will give another opportunity to explore additional opportunities.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, all jobcentres in the East End of Glasgow currently engage with Citizens Advice, Connect, Legacy Hub and Greater Easterhouse Supporting Hands.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-12T14:17:21.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756309/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756309/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756309/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent discussions he has had with third-sector organisations on the closure of Easterhouse Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","8076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756310","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>As of April 2017, there were 2,460 households in Glasgow East constituency who had a deduction made from their Housing Benefit due to the removal of the spare room subsidy. Of these, there were 1,850 where the claimant or partner was receiving Disability Living Allowance (DLA) or Personal Independence Payment (PIP) or Employment and Support Allowance (ESA).</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-12T16:20:31.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756310/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756310/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756310/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Housing Benefit: Glasgow East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people with disabilities in Glasgow East constituency had a deduction made from their benefits due to removal of the spare room subsidy in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756311","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-12","<p>In May 2017, the parliamentary constituency with the largest total weekly amount deducted from benefit claimants owing to the removal of the spare room subsidy was West Dunbartonshire. The total weekly amount deducted in this constituency was 35.7 thousand pounds.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-09-12T16:22:39.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756311/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756311/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756311/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Housing Benefit: Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, in which parliamentary constituency the largest total weekly amount was deducted from benefit claimants owing to removal of the spare room subsidy in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756312","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>At this point in time there are no DWP employees who are currently based at Easterhouse Jobcentre who are at risk of redundancy as a result of the planned closure.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-09-11T16:54:27.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756312/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756312/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756312/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Jobcentres: Glasgow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether any of his Department's staff will be offered voluntary redundancies as a result of the decision to close Easterhouse Jobcentre.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756313","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-11","<p>As set out in my answer of 30 June 2017 to Question 102, the BEIS Ministerial Team has undertaken several visits across Scotland this year, as part of the Department’s stakeholder engagement for an Industrial Strategy that works for the whole of the UK and drives growth right across the country.</p><p>This included hosting a reception at Edinburgh University on 11 April, which was attended by over 100 businesses from all over Scotland. This was followed by visits in the region.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-11T16:42:18.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756313/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756313/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756313/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Domestic Visits: Glasgow East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 30 June 2017 to Question 102, on which date (a) he and (b) a Minister of his Department last visited a company in Scotland which is headquartered specifically in Glasgow East constituency.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","7643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756314","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-12","<p>The number of recalls to prison that were fixed-term, in England and Wales for the period April 2016 to March 2017 was <strong>7,515</strong></p><p> </p><p>The only basis for recall is the breach of one or more licence conditions. In some cases, this may involve further offending. The information in the table below is taken from table 5.10 of the licence recalls workbook (https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/offender-management-statistics-quarterly-january-to-march-2017). Whereas the published table provides reason for recall for all recalled offenders, the table below only includes prisoners who have been recalled on a fixed term recall.</p><p> </p><p>Anyone who commits a crime while on licence may face prosecution and potentially more time in prison. For more serious offences, they can be held in prison on remand until trial.</p><p> </p><p>Shorter fixed-term recalls are only issued to offenders who don’t pose a risk of serious harm to the public.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Recall Period</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Apr 2016 to </strong> <strong>Mar 2017</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Further Charge</p></td><td><p>2,795</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-compliance</p></td><td><p>2,951</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Failed to keep in touch</p></td><td><p>4,524</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Failed to reside</p></td><td><p>1,487</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Drugs/alcohol</p></td><td><p>442</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other</p></td><td><p>744</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The figures in these tables have been drawn from administrative IT systems which, as with any large scale recording system, are subject to possible errors with data entry and processing. Recall reasons do not sum to the total number of recalls as more than one reason can be recorded against each recall.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-12T08:47:47.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756314/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756314/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756314/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Reoffenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many offenders received a fixed-term recall for (a) breaching the terms of their licence, (b) committing a further offence, (c) a combination of breaching their licence and reoffending and (d) any other reason in the latest year for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","7902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756315","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-09-12","<p>Veterans First Point (V1P) was established in 2013 to work with local NHS partnerships to provide a range of mental health support, information and signposting. The closure of V1P Grampian, including its funding, is a matter for V1P, the Scottish Government and NHS Grampian rather than the Ministry of Defence.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-09-12T13:46:15.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756315/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756315/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756315/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-09-04","Veterans: Charities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what representations his Department has received on the closure of the Veteran's First Point charity service in the Grampian region; and if he will make representations to the Scottish Government to encourage it to fund that service.","false","Biography information for Ross Thomson","Aberdeen South","Ross Thomson","7528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756316","Home Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The close historic, social and cultural ties between the UK and Ireland have led to the creation of additional rights above those associated with common membership of the EU. Leaders in the UK and Ireland have confirmed their commitment to protecting these rights enjoyed by UK and Irish nationals when in the other State.</p><p>As outlined in the UK Government policy paper released on 26 June, relating to the rights of EU citizens living in the UK, we want to protect the rights enjoyed by UK and Irish nationals when in the other State. Irish citizens residing in the UK will not be required to apply for settled status to protect their entitlements.</p><p>While the special status afforded to Irish citizens within the UK is rooted in the Ireland Act 1949 it has been provided for by subsequent primary and secondary legislation, including the Immigration Act 1971, and UK-Ireland bilateral agreements which are distinct from EEA Treaty rights.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-09-11T16:51:57.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756316/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756316/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756316/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-09-04","EU Nationals: Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what status citizens of the Republic of Ireland will have in the UK after the UK leaves the EU; and whether she plans to review the Ireland Act 1949.","false","Biography information for Ross Thomson","Aberdeen South","Ross Thomson","7832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756317","Department of Health","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government published its response to the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health on 9 January 2017. The Government accepted all the report’s recommendations and published a detailed and robust action plan for taking them forward, including how we will monitor progress and report this transparently.</p><p> </p><p>By 2020/21 there will be over £1 billion of extra investment every year, and the Government’s ambition is that as a result, each year, one million more people with mental health problems will access high quality care that they are not receiving today.</p><p> </p><p>For children and young people, the Department of Health is working with the Department for Education to produce a Green Paper on Children and Young People’s Mental Health, and to make Mental Health First Aid training available in primary and secondary schools. The Department of Health and NHS England will develop service capacity so that, by 2021, no child will be sent away from their local area to be treated for a general mental health condition.</p><p> </p><p>For working age adults, the Prime Minister has asked Lord Stevenson, who has campaigned on these issues for many years, and Paul Farmer, CEO of Mind and Chair of the NHS Mental Health Taskforce, to work with leading employer and mental health groups to create a new mental health partnership with industry, and make prevention and breaking stigma priorities for employers. The Government is also undertaking a full review of employment discrimination laws for employees with mental health problems.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England is investing £67.7 million in digital mental health services to expand rapidly the treatment available.</p><p>The Department is also making available up to £15 million additional funding available to support community clinics, crisis cafes, and alternative places of safety, to support preventative services in the community; and is investing over £10 million to support the fast track Think Ahead programme for mental health social workers.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-12T14:29:17.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756317/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756317/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756317/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent steps the Government has taken to improve support for people with mental health issues.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","7838"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756318","Department of Health","false","2017-09-12","<p>Improving mental health services for all is a priority for this Government but we are aware of the importance of addressing mental health issues with specific regard to men. We promote innovation in developing mental health services and interventions focused on men including programmes such as State of Mind and the Men’s Sheds movement. We are aware that suicide is the biggest killer of men under 50 and therefore in the updated National Suicide Prevention Strategy published in January we set out ways in which we are strengthening delivery of the strategy’s aims such as better targeting of high risk groups, such as men. This is supported by every local authority implementing a local suicide prevention plan by the end of 2017. Guidance issued to local authorities by Public Health England last year sets out the importance of targeting men, as a high risk group, in local suicide prevention plans.</p><p> </p><p>£12 million has been allocated between 2016/20 in Time to Change to challenge mental health stigma, which has reached 750, 000 children and young people through social marketing campaigns and improved attitudes of over 4.1 million people in England. Their latest campaign, In Your Corner, is specifically targeted at men.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-12T14:20:36.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756318/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756318/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756318/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","Mental Health: Males","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent steps the Government has taken to raise awareness of male mental health issues.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","7839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756319","Department of Health","false","2017-09-12","<p>National and regional data on waiting times for children and young people with an eating disorder are collected and published by NHS England and are available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/cyped-waiting-times/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/statistics/statistical-work-areas/cyped-waiting-times/</a></p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-12T14:31:06.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756319/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756319/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756319/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","Eating Disorders: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the average waiting times are for people with an eating disorder aged 19 and under to receive treatment in (a) Colne Valley, (b) Kirklees, (c) West Yorkshire and (d) England.","false","Biography information for Thelma Walker","Colne Valley","Thelma Walker","7840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756320","Department of Health","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government has written to recipients of the ex gratia schemes which provide financial and other types of support to those affected by HIV and/or hepatitis C through treatment with National Health Service-supplied blood or blood products before September 1991, seeking their views on the scope, format and sponsorship of the inquiry. This includes recipients in Wales, England, Scotland and Northern Ireland.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-12T14:36:17.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756320/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756320/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756320/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to consult in Wales on establishing terms of reference for the inquiry into contaminated blood.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","7612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756321","Department of Health","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government is working with the devolved administrations to ensure that they are fully consulted in developing the Terms of Reference for the inquiry into contaminated blood, particularly given the Government’s intention that the inquiry should cover the whole United Kingdom as the events in question pre-date devolution. UK Government officials are in regular contact with officials in the devolved administrations about the inquiry.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-12T14:35:28.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756321/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756321/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756321/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to work with the devolved administrations in Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland on setting the terms of reference for the inquiry into contaminated blood.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","7613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756322","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-11","<p>The proposed new prison at Port Talbot is part of our plans to reform and modernise the prison estate. We will work closely with our partners in the NHS in Wales and the Welsh Government to plan for quality health services for this new prison. No decisions have yet been made on arrangements for these services.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","7611","2017-09-11T13:14:18.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756322/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756322/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756322/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Prisons: Port Talbot","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of healthcare at the proposed Port Talbot prison will be provided by (a) the NHS and (b) private healthcare providers.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","7621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756323","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-11","<p>As of 30 June 2017, the number of category C prisoners at HM Prison and Young Offender Institutions Cardiff, Parc and Swansea were 440, 1,173 and 247 respectively.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-11T13:39:11.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756323/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756323/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756323/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Prisoners: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many Category C prisoners are held in (a) HMP Swansea, (b) HMP Cardiff and (c) HMP Parc.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","7622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756324","Department of Health","false","2017-09-12","<p>The information requested is not collected centrally.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-12T14:44:19.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756324/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756324/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756324/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","Prisoners: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many prisoners have required (a) medical treatment and (b) emergency medical treatment at an NHS hospital at (i) HMP Parc, (ii) HMP Bure and (iii) HMP The Mount in the past 24 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","7623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756325","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-11","<p>Safety and security in prisons is our top priority, and we take the mental health and wellbeing of prisoners and staff extremely seriously. The precise information requested could only be obtained at a disproportionate cost.</p><p>There is published data on the number of self-harm incidents, assaults by prisoners on other prisoners and assaults by prisoners on staff at each prison establishment within the Safety in Custody statistics, available at https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-update-to-march-2017</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-09-11T13:12:54.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756325/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756325/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756325/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Prisons: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners have caused (a) harm to themselves, (b) harm to other prisoners and (c) harm to members of the prison service in (i) HMP Parc, (ii) HMP Bure and (iii) HMP The Mount in the past 24 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","7624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756326","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-09-11","<p>The proposed new prison at Port Talbot is part of our plans to reform and modernise the prison estate. We will work closely with our partners in the NHS in Wales and the Welsh Government to plan for quality health services for this new prison. No decisions have yet been made on arrangements for these services.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","7621","2017-09-11T13:14:18.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756326/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756326/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756326/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-09-04","Prisons: Port Talbot","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what funds he will make available to the Abertawe Bro Morgannwg to provide healthcare for prisoners in the proposed prison in Port Talbot.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","7611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756327","Wales Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The procedure for funding the devolved administrations is set out in the Statement of Funding Policy; the Barnett Formula applies to changes in UK Government spend on devolved matters in England. The decision to allocate extra resource to Northern Ireland has resulted in no change to UK Government spend in England and therefore there are no Barnett consequentials. A new fiscal framework was agreed with the Welsh Government in December 2016, which enhanced Wales funding settlement.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns","7626","2017-09-11T10:34:40.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756327/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756327/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756327/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-04","Public Expenditure: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what assessment he has made of the effect of Northern Ireland's additional funding on the operation of the Barnett Formula.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","7618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756328","Wales Office","false","2017-09-11","<p>The procedure for funding the devolved administrations is set out in the Statement of Funding Policy; the Barnett Formula applies to changes in UK Government spend on devolved matters in England. The decision to allocate extra resource to Northern Ireland has resulted in no change to UK Government spend in England and therefore there are no Barnett consequentials. A new fiscal framework was agreed with the Welsh Government in December 2016, which enhanced Wales funding settlement.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns","7618","2017-09-11T10:34:40.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756328/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756328/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756328/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-09-04","Public Expenditure: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on Barnett consequential funding since the Government announced separate additional funding for Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","7626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756329","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>By design, Universal Credit is a much simpler system than that it replaces. It is easier for claimants to understand their entitlements and easier to administer. Nonetheless, we recognise that it represents a significant change for claimants, and some will find it challenging. That is why Universal Credit has an unprecedented level of personalised support for each claimant and there are a number of safeguards to support them, especially at the start of the claim. For example advances are available to help people manage until their first payment, this can amount to 50% of their indicative award and is payable straight away.</p><p> </p><p>Furthermore, ‘Universal Support’ is being rolled out alongside Universal Credit and is being delivered via a framework approach to allow third sector organisations and Local Authorities to work with jobcentres to deliver the support needed in their local community. The aim is for claimants to receive integrated tailored support journeys and partners can achieve this through best use of local resources.</p><p> </p><p>Part of this offer is budgeting support to help claimants manage their money on a monthly basis, pay bills on time and take responsibility for housing costs. Advice is offered by external organisations with the relevant expertise, online, by phone or face-to-face. Where claimants need help making a claim online, ‘assisted digital’ support is available as part of the package, alongside telephone and face to face support. And for claimants who cannot manage their money on a monthly basis alternative payment arrangements are available. These can include payment of rent direct to a landlord, paying Universal Credit more frequently or splitting the payment between members of the household.</p><p> </p><p>When debt problems are identified then the claimant can be referred on or signposted to other more specialised debt support services</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","7441 ; 7615","2017-09-11T16:48:48.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756329/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756329/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756329/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of introducing a comprehensive support package or strategy for those negatively affected by the roll-out of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","7614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756330","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>By design, Universal Credit is a much simpler system than that it replaces. It is easier for claimants to understand their entitlements and easier to administer. Nonetheless, we recognise that it represents a significant change for claimants, and some will find it challenging. That is why Universal Credit has an unprecedented level of personalised support for each claimant and there are a number of safeguards to support them, especially at the start of the claim. For example advances are available to help people manage until their first payment, this can amount to 50% of their indicative award and is payable straight away.</p><p> </p><p>Furthermore, ‘Universal Support’ is being rolled out alongside Universal Credit and is being delivered via a framework approach to allow third sector organisations and Local Authorities to work with jobcentres to deliver the support needed in their local community. The aim is for claimants to receive integrated tailored support journeys and partners can achieve this through best use of local resources.</p><p> </p><p>Part of this offer is budgeting support to help claimants manage their money on a monthly basis, pay bills on time and take responsibility for housing costs. Advice is offered by external organisations with the relevant expertise, online, by phone or face-to-face. Where claimants need help making a claim online, ‘assisted digital’ support is available as part of the package, alongside telephone and face to face support. And for claimants who cannot manage their money on a monthly basis alternative payment arrangements are available. These can include payment of rent direct to a landlord, paying Universal Credit more frequently or splitting the payment between members of the household.</p><p> </p><p>When debt problems are identified then the claimant can be referred on or signposted to other more specialised debt support services</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","7441 ; 7614","2017-09-11T16:48:48.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756330/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756330/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756330/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what support his Department provides for universal credit claimants for (a) budgeting, (b) managing a claim online and (c) complex claims.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","7615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756331","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>Any need for an advance payment or other financial or budgeting support should be established at the outset of a claim for Universal Credit. This includes existing benefit claimants who move to Universal Credit through a change of circumstances. In the initial new claim interview, work coaches are trained to offer personal budgeting support and assess whether claimants need help to manage until their first Universal Credit payment. If so they are advised to apply for an advance. Furthermore, additional work has been done by the Department to raise awareness of advances nationally, including providing options on the UC Helpline, and signposting through the new “Universal Credit &amp; you” guide for claimants and on the new online Money Manager tool offered by the Money Advice Service. We will shortly be publishing data on advances.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","7326 ; 7497 ; 7617 ; 9501","2017-09-11T14:26:31.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756331/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756331/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756331/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Universal Credit: Payments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of advice given by (a) work coaches and (b) universal credit journals on claiming the advance payment of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","7616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756332","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-09-11","<p>Any need for an advance payment or other financial or budgeting support should be established at the outset of a claim for Universal Credit. This includes existing benefit claimants who move to Universal Credit through a change of circumstances. In the initial new claim interview, work coaches are trained to offer personal budgeting support and assess whether claimants need help to manage until their first Universal Credit payment. If so they are advised to apply for an advance. Furthermore, additional work has been done by the Department to raise awareness of advances nationally, including providing options on the UC Helpline, and signposting through the new “Universal Credit &amp; you” guide for claimants and on the new online Money Manager tool offered by the Money Advice Service. We will shortly be publishing data on advances.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","7326 ; 7497 ; 7616 ; 9501","2017-09-11T14:26:31.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756332/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756332/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756332/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-09-04","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the levels of uptake of advance payment of universal credit in (a) the UK, (b) Wales and (c) Aberavon constituency.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kinnock","Aberavon","Stephen Kinnock","7617"
