"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756335","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>Modern companies rely on many stakeholders to be successful, including shareholders, employees and wider society. The UK already has a requirement in existing company law that these wider stakeholders be taken into account. To ensure companies are taking advantage of this best practice, the government will require Directors to explain how they are representing the interests of wider stakeholders. In addition, the government has asked the Financial Reporting Council to examine potential changes to the corporate governance code in order to further strengthen the voice of stakeholders.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-12T13:45:37.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756335/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756335/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756335/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Industrial Democracy","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress the Government is making on its plans for changes in the structure of employee representation; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","7769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756336","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>A clear, dependable and modern corporate governance framework is one of the major strengths of the UK as a place to do business and further transparency can help strengthen this framework further. The government recently announced its plan to modernise the corporate governance framework, which will include requiring public companies to publish ratios of the difference in pay between the CEO and the average worker.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-09-12T13:44:48.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756336/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756336/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756336/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Managers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress the Government is making on its plans for increased transparency on executive pay; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","7770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756337","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government is committed to tackling tax avoidance and evasion at all levels to ensure everyone, no matter who they are, pays the right amount of tax at the right time.</p><p> </p><p>Our strategy is working. Last year, HMRC brought in a record additional £29 billion by cracking down on avoidance, evasion and non-compliance. At 6.5%, the UK’s tax gap is one of the lowest in the world.</p><p> </p><p>And we are legislating for over ten measures in the upcoming Finance Bill to further crackdown on those who try to avoid or evade paying the tax that is owed.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-12T13:26:14.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756337/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756337/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756337/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the Government's strategy to tackle tax avoidance; and what recent estimate he has made of the effect of that strategy on the revenues derived from overall taxation.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","7768"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756338","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-08","<p>The Government will publish the outcome of its review in due course.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-08T14:19:51.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756338/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756338/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756338/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Mergers and Takeovers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what progress the Government is making on its plans for new policies on mergers and takeovers; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","7752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756339","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government continues to consider options for regulation to tackle tax avoidance and evasion at all levels to ensure everyone, no matter who they are, pays the right amount of tax at the right time. Tax advisory firms have a key role to play in tackling these risks.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has committed to set up a new Office of Professional Body Anti-Money Laundering Supervision at the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA). Sectors at risk of being used to facilitate money laundering and terrorist financing are supervised by 25 organisations, 22 of which are professional bodies for accountancy and providers of legal services.</p><p> </p><p>Last year, HMRC brought in a record additional £29 billion by cracking down on avoidance, evasion and non-compliance and we continue to explore what more we can do to reduce what is already one of the lowest tax gaps in the world.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-12T12:49:57.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756339/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756339/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756339/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Taxation: Advisory Bodies","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress the Government is making on its plans for increased regulation of tax advisory firms; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","7753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756340","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>At Budget 2016, the Government announced a package of measures to tackle VAT non-compliance by overseas businesses that sell goods via online marketplaces to UK customers.</p><p> </p><p>We took swift action to make online marketplaces jointly and severally liable for the unpaid VAT of overseas sellers. We also announced the introduction of the fulfilment house due diligence scheme. This is on track to open for registration next year. Together these two measures will deliver £875 million for the Exchequer by 2021.</p><p> </p><p>At Spring Budget 2017, the Government published a call for evidence on the case for a new VAT collection mechanism for online sales by overseas sellers. This would harness technology to allow VAT to be extracted directly by the Exchequer from online transactions at the point of purchase. This means the VAT would never get into the hands of the overseas seller.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-12T13:27:44.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756340/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756340/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756340/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Cybercrime: VAT","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress the Government is making on its plans for measures to reduce online fraud in VAT; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","7754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756341","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The government is working with businesses and local authorities to deliver its aim to move to more frequent revaluations. The government will then set out its preferred approach for a smoother and more frequent system of revaluation.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-12T13:28:44.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756341/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756341/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756341/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what progress the Government is making on its plans for changes in business rates and self-evaluations; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","7755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756342","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government is committed to improving tax transparency, and working with the financial sector and other intermediaries to achieve this objective.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has led the way in delivering the global Common Reporting Standard (CRS) which means foreign financial account providers have an obligation to report the accounts of UK resident taxpayers.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has also strengthened the Code of Practice on Taxation for Banks in 2013, so that banks’ commitments not to engage in or promote UK tax avoidance can be better enforced.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-12T13:37:02.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756342/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756342/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756342/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to work with banks and the financial sector to improve tax transparency.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","7760"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756343","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Crown Dependencies and Overseas Territories (CDOTs) are self-governing with democratically elected governments who are responsible for fiscal matters. All CDOTs with a financial centre are committed to agreed global standards on tax transparency.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-12T10:16:35.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756343/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756343/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756343/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Taxation: British Overseas Territories","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to help improve the tax transparency of Crown Dependencies and Overseas Territories.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","7761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756344","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>I refer the Hon. Member for Hayes and Harlington to the written answers given on 6 September 2017 to his previous questions on the subject.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","7763 ; 7764","2017-09-12T12:40:55.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756344/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756344/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756344/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Overseas Residence: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to tackle tax avoidance and tax evasion by people and companies conducted by means of trusts which transfer trustees' residence offshore.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","7762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756345","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The UK is seeking multilateral agreement on a model of public country-by-country reporting (CBCR).</p><p> </p><p>It is important that there is a level of international support and co-ordination that leads to both domestic and foreign headquartered groups being required to report information for a comprehensive range of countries in which they operate.</p><p> </p><p>The UK has raised public CBCR with international partners and will continue to do so, including at EU level.</p><p> </p><p>The Government remains determined to get the very best deal for businesses and households during the negotiations with the EU.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","7126","2017-09-12T12:43:30.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756345/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756345/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756345/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Taxation: Multinational Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that multinational firms file public reports on their dealings, country by country; and whether these steps affect the UK's negotiations strategy on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","7759"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756346","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>I refer the Hon. Member for Hayes and Harlington to the written answers given on 6 September 2017 to his previous questions on the subject.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","7762 ; 7764","2017-09-12T12:40:55.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756346/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756346/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756346/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Trusts: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the loss of revenue to the public purse resulting from (a) tax avoidance and (b) tax evasion by people and companies via trusts.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","7763"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756347","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>I refer the Hon. Member for Hayes and Harlington to the written answers given on 6 September 2017 to his previous questions on the subject.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","7762 ; 7763","2017-09-12T12:40:55.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756347/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756347/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756347/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Trusts: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment his Department has made of the effectiveness of mechanisms to monitor beneficiaries or controllers of trust assets in respect of (a) tax avoidance and (b) tax evasion.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","7764"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756348","Department of Health","false","2017-09-12","<p>The National Minimum Wage is the legal minimum employers must pay their workers. The Government is committed to creating an economy that works for everyone, and ensuring workers are paid fairly. It is the responsibility of all employers to pay the correct minimum wage to their staff, and HM Revenue and Customs takes enforcement action against those who do not.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has received many representations from social care providers about the implications of being required to pay penalties or arrears relating to underpayment of the National Minimum Wage. The Government will waive the financial penalties faced by employers who are found to have underpaid their workers for “sleep-in” shifts. The waiver is to apply to any arrears of pay resulting from “sleep-in” shifts that took place before 26 July 2017.</p><p>The Government will continue to work with representatives of the social care sector to see how it might be possible to minimise any impact on provision of social care as a result of this situation. To allow this work to take place before deadlines of arrears of wages are enforced, the Government has adopted a policy of temporarily suspending enforcement activity of “sleep-in” shifts. This suspension will apply until 2 October 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The stability of the social care sector is a key Government priority. Consequently, at the Spring Budget the Government announced that it was providing an additional £2 billion to councils in England for social care, including £1 billion this year.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-09-12T16:18:24.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756348/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756348/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756348/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-09-04","Carers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department has taken to ensure that social care providers can pay their staff rates above those set for the national minimum wage (a) generally and (b) for sleep-in shift arrangements.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","7765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756349","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Government has more than trebled annual funding of minimum wage enforcement since 2014.</p><p> </p><p>All businesses, irrespective of size or business sector, are responsible for paying the correct minimum wage to their staff. The Government is determined that everyone who is entitled to the National Minimum Wage (NMW) and National Living Wage (NLW) receives it.</p><p> </p><p>Anyone who feels they have been underpaid NMW or NLW should contact the Acas helpline on 0300 123 1100. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) review all complaints that are referred to them. Additionally, HMRC collate and analyse data from various sources in order to identify those employers who are potentially more likely to be underpaying NMW or NLW, so that they can undertake targeted enforcement against those employers.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-12T13:32:49.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756349/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756349/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756349/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Charities: Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department has taken to ensure that national minimum wage regulations are being properly enforced in the charities sector (a) generally and (b) for sleep-in shift arrangements.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","7766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756350","HM Treasury","false","2017-09-12","<p>In the 2015 Summer Budget, the Government announced investment of £800 million to tackle non‑compliance, including £266 million and 670 new staff to tackle tax fraud.</p><p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) are doing more to tackle organised criminals evading tax and duties and are tripling the number of criminal investigations into the most serious and complex tax crimes.</p><p>To tackle enablers of offshore tax evasion, new civil sanctions have been introduced to include public naming and penalties of up to 100% of the tax evaded.</p><p>In addition new criminal offences to address corporate complicity in facilitating tax evasion were legislated for in the Criminal Finances Act 2017. These offences take effect from 30 September 2017.</p><p>This all builds on our earlier investment in HMRC which enabled it to achieve a seven-fold increase in the number of prosecutions over the Spending Review 2010 period.</p><p>Last year this work protected over £2.3bn of vital public revenue.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-09-12T13:34:53.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756350/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756350/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756350/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-09-04","Tax Evasion: Prosecutions","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to increase the number of successful prosecutions for tax evasion; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","7767"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756351","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-08","<p>The detriment to retail energy customers on poor value standard variable tariffs, which was identified by the Competition and Market Authority as averaging £1.4bn a year, must be addressed.</p><p>My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State has written to the Chief Executive of Ofgem asking him to advise on what action the regulator intends to take to safeguard consumers on the poorest value tariffs and to consider the future of standard variable tariffs. The Secretary of State will consider further action in the light of Ofgem’s proposals and remains prepared to legislate if necessary.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-08T14:22:38.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756351/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756351/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756351/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Energy: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what progress the Government is making on its plans for the introduction of a cap on energy bills; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","7756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756352","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-07","<p>My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State wrote to the CEO of Ofgem on 21 June asking him to advise on what action the regulator might take to protect consumers on the poorest value tariffs and to consider the future of standard variable tariffs. The Department has not undertaken an equality impact assessment on the introduction of a cap on energy bills. The Secretary of State will decide on how to proceed when he has considered Ofgem’s proposals.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-07T14:11:58.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756352/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756352/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756352/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Energy: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what equality impact assessment his Department has undertaken on the introduction of a cap on energy bills; and if he will place a copy of that assessment in the Library.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","7757"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756353","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-09-07","<p>My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State wrote to the CEO of Ofgem on 21 June asking him to advise on what action the regulator intends to take to safeguard consumers on the poorest value tariffs and to consider the future of standard variable tariffs. The Secretary of State will decide on how to proceed, including on whether any additional analysis is necessary, when he has considered Ofgem’s proposals.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-09-07T14:10:10.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756353/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756353/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756353/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-09-04","Energy: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what distributional analysis his Department has undertaken on the introduction of a cap on energy bills; and if he will place a copy of that analysis in the Library.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","7758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756354","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-12","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply previously given on 24 July 2017, PQ 5522.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-12T12:44:37.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756354/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756354/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756354/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-04","Pets: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to the Answer of 20 April 2017 to Question 70622, for what reason the data recorded on the Pets Database and presented in the Answer to Question 66537 was inaccurate; and what the margin of error was in that data.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","8192"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756355","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-09-12","<p>The Animal and Plant Health Agency (APHA) agree a Required Method of Operation (RMOP) with transport companies which carry pet animals. The RMOP includes protocols to capture data accurately and to submit it in a timely manner. In the absence of an electronic method of data capture, manual entry is often the only current option. Whilst there is no legislative power to enforce data collection APHA work closely with the transport companies to ensure that they understand the need for accuracy.</p><p> </p><p>A new electronic method of collecting data is being considered where APHA hope to build on technological approaches being developed for other purposes.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-09-12T16:29:56.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756355/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756355/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756355/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-09-04","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 24 July 2017 to Question 5522, (a) what steps he is taking to phase out manual data entry and (b) whether his Department is considering methods of data entry to improve the accuracy of data collection.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","8281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/756356","Attorney General","false","2017-09-13","<p>The records that the Attorney General’s Office holds reveal the following data in relation to rape offences.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Please note that these figures include referrals for sentences passed for rape offences charged under the 1956 Sexual Offences Act (for offences committed prior to the commencement of the 2003 Act but which were not sentenced until 2009 or afterwards) as well as for rape offences charged under the provisions of the Sexual Offences Act 2003. It is of course likely that a high proportion of the referrals received by my office from the CPS will have been submitted with the full support of the victim.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Year</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Referrals to AGO made by Victim </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Referrals to AGO made by CPS</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Referred by AG or SG to CoA</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Considered ULS by the court</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Referrals where sentence increased</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2009</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>0</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>9</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>6</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>6</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>0</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>18</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>8</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>6</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>6</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>0</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>7</strong></p></td